column168: SPILL RESPONSE TEAM WAS CALLED TO SORT 2, TRACK 108 AT 0222L ON A POSSIBLE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL FOUND 1 5-GALLON STEEL DRUM THAT WAS DAMAGED AND CONTENTS SPILLED OUT.  SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED IN A 55-GALLON DISPOSAL DRUM AND PLACED IN THE WASTE BUILDING AWAITING DISPOSITION BY THE ENVIRONMENTAL AFFAIRS DEPT.

A VAN TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM ALUMINUM COMPANY OF AMERICA LOCATED AT 3000 STATE STREET IN LEBANON, PA TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. IN CHICAGO, IL.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP, THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS OF BALTIMORE, INC. LOCATED AT 1910 RUSSELL STREET, IN ORDER TO TRANSFER CONTAINERS TO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION.  DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRANSFER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 1/2 PINT OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM A PINHOLE LEAK THAT HAD DEVELOPED ON THE BOTTOM OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE VAN TRAILER WHERE IT WAS PREVENTED FROM ESCAPING TO THE ENVIRONMENT.  FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SUITABLE SALVAGE DRUM.  ALL CLEAN-UP DEBRIS WAS PLACED INTO THE SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION IDENTIFIED THAT A SMALL DENT WAS PRESENT ON THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM THAT IS ASSUMED TO HAVE BEEN CAUSED BY THE DRUM BEING DROPPED.  PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOCATION, ALL DRUMS WERE VISUALLY INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED.  THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO THOROUGHLY INSPECT EACH DRUM AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A DAMAGED DRUM IS IDENTIFIED.

column168: DEFECTIVE VALVE ON THE TOTE TANK ALLOWED CLEANER TO LEAK OUT INTO INBOUND TRL.  CLEANER WAS SOAKED UP WITH OIL DRY AND TOTE WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE WITH CONSIGNEE MAKING NO NOTATIONS OF DAMAGES OR LOSSES.

FEDEX COURIER DIANA WATSON WAS AT THE SHIPPER LOCATION MAKING THE PICK UP. AS SHE PICKED UP THE BOX SHE LAID THE BOX SIDEWAYS TO CARRY IT OUT OF THE BUILDING. WHEN SHE DID, THE FREE-STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE DEWAR FLOWED OUT OF THE VENTED CAP STRIKING HER ARM. THIS CAUSED NEARLY IMMEDIATE SECOND DEGREE BURNS. DIANA RETURNED TO THE SHIPPING AREA, DROPPED THE BOX, LEFT THE FACILITY AND SOUGHT IMMEDIATE MEDICAL ATTENTION. UPON BEING RELEASED FROM THE CLINIC AND BEING TREATED FOR HER WOUND, DIANA RESUMED HER PICK UP ROUTE. SHE AGAIN WENT TO THE SHIPPING LOCATION AND PICKED UP THE BOX. SHE WAS TOLD BY DR. HARRIS THAT THERE WAS NO MORE FREE-STANDING LIQUID NITROGEN IN THE PACKAGE. ONCE DIANA RETURNED TO THE CONROE FEDEX STATION I WAS ADVISED. I TOLD LISA BASS, DIANA'S MANAGER, TO HOLD FREIGHT AT THE STATION UNTIL THE FAA COULD DETERMINE IF AN INVESTIGATION WOULD BE PURSUED. I SPOKE WITH THE FAA'S SOUTHWEST REGION DANGEROUS GOODS COORDINATOR STEVE BRASHER. I ADVISED WHAT HAD TRANSPIRED. STEVE REQUESTED THAT THE FREIGHT HE HELD. UN UNIDENTIFIED FAA SPECIAL AGENT MET DIANA AT HER CLINIC TODAY TAKE PICTURES OF HER WOUNDS AND THEN TAKE MORE PHOTOS OF THE IMPOUNDED FREIGHT. I SPOKED WITH TOM LEE FROM THE SHIPPER AS WELL AS DR. HARRIS. I TOLD THEM THAT THE FREIGHT WOULD BE RELEASED TO THEM ONCE THE FAA RELEASES IT. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.
THE PACKAGE WAS DROPPED AND LEAKED FROM THE TOP. THE DG/SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST PERFORMED ALL PROPER SPILL CLEANUP FUNCTIONS THEN CONTAINED THE PACKAGE IN A SALVAGE DRUM PENDING DISPOSITION.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE RELOAD WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED. THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY PUNCTURED FROM A PROTUSION FROM ANOTHER PACKAGE. THIS ALLOWED APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE TO BE RELEASED FROM THE CONTAINER. THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ACCORDING TO PROCEDURE. THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE INBOUND AM PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE LEAKAGE WAS NOTICED. THE SHIPMENT WAS ISOLATED, OPENED AND EXAMINED TO REVEAL A GLASS BOTTLE ON THE INSIDE. THE CAP SEAL HAD APPARENTLY FAILED AND THIS ALLOWED THE RELEASE OF APPROXIMATELY ONE OUNCE OF THE MATERIAL. THE SUBSTANCE SMELLED LIKE DIESEL FUEL. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AND THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED. THE SHIPPER BASICALLY IMPLIED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WAS SOME TYPE OF FURNACE OIL. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

CAR INSPECTORS DETECTED ODOR OF PROPANE WHILE MAKING ROUTINE INSPECTION IN TRAIN YARD. BNSF RESPONDERS FOUND "A" END LIQUID VALVE COMPLETELY ICED. THE VALVE HANDLE WAS OPEN 1/4 TURN AND THE PLUG WAS LOOSE. AFTER DEICING THE VALVE, IT WAS FULLY CLOSED AND THE PLUG WAS FULLY TIGHTENED WITH 10 TO 12 TURNS. THE LIQUID LPG/PROPANE IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS ALLOWED TO BOIL AWAY. THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AFTER FURTHER OBSERVATION.

column168: THE GLENDALE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO A CITIZEN'S CALL THAT REPORTED THE STENCH OF NATURAL GAS. THIS TANK CAR WAS FOUND TO BE VENTING THROUGH THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE ON AN INTERMITTENT BASIS. AN EVACUATION OF TWO BLOCKS WAS MADE AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE. APPROXIMATELY 10 PEOPLE WERE INVOLVED AS THIS OCCURED IN AN INDUSTRIAL AREA ON A SUNDAY. ** BNSF RESPONDERS AND FIRE DEPARTMENT MEMBERS MONITORED THE CAR. A RAIN SHOWER BROUGHT COOLING FROM THE 105F AMBIENT TEMP. WHEN FIRST FOUND. AS VENTING CEASED, THE SITUATION WAS ENDED AT 2000 HOURS. TWO TRAINS WERE DELAYED DURING THE PERIOD OF SUSPENDED OPERATIONS. THE CAR WAS SPOTTED FOR UNLOADING.
EXTERNAL VALVE WAS LEAKING PUT - BUCKET UNDER. DRIVER CHANGED GASKET AND LEAK STOPPED. SPILL REPORTED TO MANAGER OF REST AREA. USED SPEEDI DRY TO CLEAN UP.
BAG OF HAZMAT WAS RIPPED WHILE LOADING.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED AND MSDS OBTAINED.  MSDS WAS RECEIVED.  HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED CLEANUP AND PLACED WASTE IN A RECOVERY DRUM.

SPILL WAS FOUND BY A SUPERVISOR ON DUTY WHO NOTICED LEAKING PRODUCT.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND MATERIAL IDENTIFIED.  SHIPPER AND CHEMTREC WERE NOTIFIED AND MSDS OBTAINED.  NEUTRALIZER WAS  APPLIED TO SPILL AND WASTE WAS THEN SHOVELED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED.  THE REMAINDER OF SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE.

STEVE DIAL FOUND THAT THE NUT ON THE SAMPLE TUVE WAS NOT TIGHT.  STEVE TIGHTENED NUT AND THAT STOPPED LEAK. SHIPPER AND ALL CONCERNED NOTIFIED, CAR REPAIRED AND RETURNED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT FROM TO POINT OF UNLOADING IT WAS DISCOVERED THE CAP WAS LOOSE AND WAS TIGHTENED WHEN IT ARRIVED.  SOME OF THE MATERIAL HAD ESCAPED ONTO THE TOP OF THE DRUM.  IT WAS FOUND THAT ONLY ABOUT 1 CUP OR LESS HAD ESCAPED.

PACKAGE WAS TAKEN TO P.S.C. BY A DESIGNATED FIRST RESPONDER WHO FOLLOWED PROPER PROCEDURE.  THE DECISION TREE WAS UTILIZED AND FOLLOWED ALONG WITH THE LIQUID CORROSIVE RESPONSE SHEET.  PROPER PPE WAS USED, SOLID WASTE NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM BICARBONATE AND TESTED WITH PH INDICATOR UNTIL 6-9 RANGE WAS OBTAINED.  PACKAGE THEN PROCESSED THROUGH DMP.

TWO(2) 30 GALLONS DRUMS WERE PICKED UP @ CUSTOMER LOCATION AND TRANSPORTED TO THE NEXT CUSTOMER LOCATION.  UPON ARRIVAL THE DRIVER DISCOVERED THAT ONE OF THE DRUMS HAD DEVELOPED A PINHOLE CORROSION LEAK IN THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM AND RELEASED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF WASTE COMUBSTIBLE LIQUID(WASTE PETROLEUM SOLVENT) INTO CONTAINMENT IN THE TRUCK.  THE RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENT AND THE FAILED DRUM CONTENTS AND THE SPILL CLEANUP MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A GOOD DRUM.  ALL RELEASED MATERIAL WAS CAPTURED IN THE TRUCK CONTAINMENT AND WAS RECOVERED.

ODOR DISCOVERED IN TRAILER UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE.  SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE ADVISED VENTING TRAILER IN REMOTE AREA.  AFTER VENTING, CONSIGNEE UNLOADED, IDENTIFIED 3 SUSPECT CYLINDERS.  THOSE 3 PLACED INTO CONSIGNEE'S SYSTEM IMMEDIATELY.  SUSPECT CYLINDERS HAVE BEEN MARKED, WILL BE EXAMINED BY SHIPPER UPON RETURN TO THEM AND PROBLEM CORRECTED BEFORE FURTHER USE.

I WAS LOADING SPENT ACID, THE CUSTOMERS METER DID NOT SHUT OFF AS IT WAS SUPPOSED TO, CAUSING THE TRAILER TO OVERFILL.  THERE WAS ABOUT 30 GALLONS OF ACID THAT GOT ONTO THE ASPHALT.  THE OPERATOR HAD ME WASH IT INTO THEIR DRAIN.  I HAD TO UNLOAD PART OF THE ACID BACK INTO THEIR TANK BECAUSE I WAS OVERLOADED.

column168: GATX39421 WAS GIVING OFF AN ODOR AT THE CAR MAINTENANCE FACILITY IN DAYTON, OH YARD.  CAR WAS MOVED TO AN ISOLATED LOCATION IN YARD.  M + R INDUSTRIAL SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO ASCERTAIN SOURCE/REASON FOR ODOR.  UPON INVESTIGATION IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE NOT TOOL TIGHT(PROPERLY TIGHTENED IN PLACE BY USE OF A BAR, WRENCH, OR OTHER TOOL).  THE MANWAY BOLTS VARIED FROM FINGER TIGHT TO FIVE REVOLUTIONS TO RESISTENCE.  THE CAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  BOTH THE SHIPPER AND CONSIGNEE WERE NOTIFIED.

TANK CAR WAS REPORTED TO SPLASH PRODUCT FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED AT CSXT'S LOCUS POINT YARD IN BALTIMORE, MD.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER AUTHORIZED A LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO RESPOND AND CORRECT THE PROBLEMS.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE CAR HAD A BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  THE CONTRACTOR REPLACED THE BLOWN DISK AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

A CAR INSPECTOR AT CSXT'S RAILYARD IN ABYCROSS, GA, NOTICED A SWEET ODOR IN THE AREA HE WAS WORKING.  FURTHER INSPECTION IDENTIFIED UTLX202033 AS THE POSSIBLE SOURCE OF THE ODOR.  A HISSING SOUND WAS HEARD COMING FROM THE MANWAY.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  CSXT SENT A RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INSPECT CAR.  CONTRACTOR FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF ANY LIQUID SPILLAGE BUT HEARD HISSING FROM THE MANWAY.  THEY RELIEVED PRESSURE ON THE CAR AND OPENED THE MANWAY.  THE GASKET HAD A CREASE IN IT.  IT WAS TURNED OVER AND INSTALLED.  THE MANWAY COVER WAS SECURED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED.

column168: CAP ON BOTTLE POPPED OFF WHEN BOX TOPPLED OFF THE TOP OF PALLET. BOX FAILED DUE TO LIQUID DAMAGE FROM SPILLED PRODUCT. BOX WAS ON SHRUNK WRAPPED PALLET LOADED INTO CENTER OF TRAILER. BOX TOPPLED OFF THE PALLET DUE TO STANDARD SHIFTING OF LOAD DURING TRANSPORT OPERATIONS. 1 GAL. PLASTIC CONTAINER INSIDE THE CARDBOARD BOX POPPED THE CAP WHEN THE BOX CONTACTED THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER IN WHICH IT WAS BEING TRANSPORTED. PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE PACKAGE AND ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. THAT PRODUCT NOT ABSORBED BY THE CARDBOARD AND WOOD FLOORING OF THE TRAILER, SEEMED THROUGH THE FLOORING AND ONTO THE GROUND.

THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE CONSIGNEE'S LOCATION, LACROSS INDUSTRIES, AND WAS TOLD BY THE RECEIVER THAT THE CONSIGNEE HAD THEIR OWN HOSE FOR THE TANK INTO WHICH THE PRODUCT WAS TO BE UNLOADED. THE DRIVER HOOKED THE END OF THE HOSE TO HIS PUMP, THE RECEIVER OPENED THE CONSIGNEE'S INBOUND LINE AND THE DRIVER STARTED HIS PUMP TO UNLOAD THE PRODUCT. AFTER PUMPING FOR APPROXIMATELY 10 MINUTES, THE CONSIGNEE TOLD THE DRIVER TO STOP PUMPING, THAT THERE WAS A SPILL. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN HIS PUMP AND, AT THAT POINT, THE DRIVER AND THE RECEIVER CHECKED THE UNLOADING HOSE. THE CONSIGNEE'S UNLOADING HOSE WAS LAYING ACROSS THE ROOF OF A SHED WITH THE END OF THE HOSE OUT OF SIGHT. THE CONSIGNEE OPENED THE SHED AND THEY SAW THAT THE HOSE WAS LOOPED OVER THE SHED, NOT CONNECTED TO ANYTHING, AND HAD BEEN ALLOWING THE PRODUCT TO RUN DOWN THE STAIRS OF THE BUILDING INTO THE BASEMENT. EMERGENCY PROCEDURES WERE INSTITUTED, THE BUILDING WAS EVACUATED AND CLEAN UP STARTED.

column168: (A & B) INTERMODAL CONTAINER NONZ 50480 WAS INVOLVED IN A MULTICAR DERAILMENT RESULTING IN DAMAGE TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGES INSIDE THE CONTAINER. THE SHIPMENT CONTAINED MIXED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS IN HAZARD CLASSES OF FLAMMABLE AND CORROSIVE INSIDE 55 GALLON DRUMS AND 5 GALLON PAILS. TWO OF THE DRUMS AND TWO PAILS WERE CRUSHED IN THE DERAILMENT AND THERE CONTENTS LOST. OTHER PACKAGES OF THE SAME TYPE WERE DAMAGED AND OVERPACKED IN SALVAGE DRUMS AS A PRECAUTION EVEN THOUGH THERE WAS NO INDICATION OF PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THOSE PACKAGES. ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS ISOLATED AND REMOVED ALL CONTAMINATED MATERIALS FOR PROPER DISPOSAL.

A TANK TRAILER CONTAINING HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS ENROUTE FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF BRAINTREE, INC. LOCATED AT 385 QUINCY AVENUE IN BRAINTREEE, MA TO CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. LOCATED AT 2900 BROADWAY IN CLEVELAND, OH. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. FACILITY PERSONNEL RECONTAINERIZED THE OIL LAYER INTO 2 X 55 GALLON CONTAINERS AND WAS INSTRUCTED BY THE SHIPPER TO REJECT HTE 2 X 55 GALLON DRUMS OF WASTE PETROLEUM OIL TO AN ALTERNATE WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY (CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. LOCATED AT 11800 S. STONEY ISLAND AVENUE IN CHICAGO, IL). *** DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRIP FROM CLEAN HARBORS OF CLEVELAND, INC. TO CLEAN HARBORS SERVICES, INC. THE DRIVER MADE A ROUTINE STOP AT CLEAN HARBORS' CLEVELAND SERVICE CENTER LOCATED AT 2940 INDEPENDENCE AVENUE IN ORDER TO TRANSFER THE CONTAINERS TO A SECOND TRANSPORT VEHICLE FOR CONTINUING TRANSPORTATION. DURING THE COURSE OF THE TRANSFER IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT APPROXIMATELY 6 OUNCES OF MATERIAL ESCAPED FROM THE TOP LID OF ONE OF THE CONTAINERS ONTO THE CONCRETE LOADING DOCK. FACILITY PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY CONTAINED THE RELEASE, ABSORBED ALL FREE LIQUIDS WITH SPEEDI DRY AND PLACED THE DAMAGED CONTAINER INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL TO THE INTENDED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY. AN INSPECTION OF THE CONTAINER IN QUESTION IDENTIFIED THAT THE GASKET USED TO CREATE A SEAL BETWEEN THE CONTAINER BODY AND THE TOP CLOSURE WAS DEFECTIVE ALLOWING MATERIAL TO ESCAPE FROM THE TOP LID WHEN THE CONTAINER WAS BEING MOVED. *** PRIOR TO DEPARTURE FROM THE SHIPPERS LOACATION, ALL DRUMS WERE VISUALLY INSPECTED AND NO EVIDENCE OF LEAKING WAS OBSERVED. THE DRIVER HAS BEEN RE-INSTRUCTED TO THOROUGHLY INSPECT EACH DRUM AS IT IS LOADED AND TAKE APPROPRIATE ACTION IN THE EVENT A DAMAGED DRUM IS IDENTIFIED.
WHILE UNLOADING TRAILER, A DRUM WAS PUNCTURED WITH A FORKLIFT. THE DRUM WAS REPAIRED AND OVERPACKED INTO A DOT APPROVED SALVAGE DRUM AND WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR CLAIMS CREDIT.

A CONTAINER OF DRUMS WAS LOADED AT THE P D GEORGE COMPANY FACILITY IN ST LOUIS.  THE CONTAINER WAS TRANSPORTED TO SEATTLE, WA BY BURLINGTON RAILROAD. WHEN THE CONTAINER  ARRIVED AT THE TERMINAL IN SEATTLE IT WAS LEAKING MATERIAL FROM THE BOTTOM. THE  CONTAINER WAS INSPECTED BY P D GEORGE PERSONNEL AND WE DISCOVERED THAT FOUR DRUMS WERE LEAKING AT THEIR LOWER CHIME AREA.  THE ENTIRE LOAD OF DRUMS WAS RETURNED TO ST  LOUIS. THE DRUM MANUFACTURER, MEYER STEEL DRUM, INC OF CHICAGO, IL WAS CONTACTED AND  THEY CONDUCTED A DRUM INSPECTION.  MEYER CONCLUDED THAT THERE WAS A MANUFACTURING  DEFECT.

column168: MCCUTHEON ENTERPRISES, INC. WAS CONTACTED BY JESSOP STEEL, WASHINGTON PA, TO LOAD AND TRANSPORT SPEND SULFURIC ACID WASTE FROM THEIR FACILITY TO MILL SERVICE, YUKON PA FOR DISPOSAL ON 5-28-97. AFTER THE TRAILER HAD BEEN TOP LOADED AT JESSOP STEEL, THE MEI DRIVER HAD SECURED THE REAR MANHOLE AND AFTER COMPLETION OF THE PENNSYLVANIA HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST, PROCEEDED ON THE 38 MILE TRIP TO MILL SERVICE. SHORTLY UPON ARRIVAL AT MILL SERVICE, MARK PENSKA, THE HOST MUNICIPALITY INSPECTOR FOR MILL SERVICE HAD NOTIFIED MILL SERVICE PERSONNEL AND PENNSYLVANIA DEP THAT THERE WAS A SPILL ON THE ROAD BEFORE ENTERING THE PLANT. WE WERE NOTIFIED BY MILL SERVICE THAT ONE OF OUR TRAILERS HAD SPILLED ACID ON THE ROAD AT ABOUT 5:00 PM AND WE PROCEED TO MOBILIZE PERSONNEL AND EQUIPMENT TO CLEAN-UP WAS COMPLETED BY 9:30 PM ON THAT SAME DAY. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE TRAILER, IT WAS EVIDENT THAT THE SPILLAGE HAD COME FROM THE REAR MANHOLE CONTAINMENT AREA. AFTER PERFORMING TIGHTNESS AND PRESSURE TESTS ON THE TRAILER, NO MECHANICAL DEFECTS HAD BEEN FOUND ON THE TRAILER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A ONE INCH PRESSURE RELEASE VALVE HAD BEEN LEFT OPEN, OR PARTIALLY OPENED, ALLOWING ACID TO SPILL INTO HIS REAR CONTAINMENT AREA AND FROM THERE, ONTO THE GROUND THROUGH THE TWO DRAINAGE TUBES COMING FROM THE CONTAINMENT AREA. BECAUSE THE LIQUID LEVEL OF THE LOAD BEING TRANSPORTED IN THE TRAILER WAS DOWN APPROXIMATELY 12", SPILLAGE OCCURRED ONLY AS THE TRAILER WAS ASCENDING HILLS. BY RECOMMENDATION OF THE PA DEP, ADDITIONAL CLEAN-UP HAD TAKEN PLACE AT THE SITE WITH A POWER SWEEPING BROOM/VACUUM UNIT ON 6-4-97. UPON INVESTIGATION OF THE ROADWAY NEAR THE JESSOP STEEL PLANT, WE FOUND SOME MINOR ADDITIONAL SPILLAGE WHICH WAS CLEANED-UP WITH THIS POWER BROOM ON 6-10-97. AS AN ACTION TO PREVENT FUTURE INCIDENTS OF THIS NATURE, THE PRESSURE RELEASE LINE, COMING FROM THE VALVE, WAS CAPPED-OFF. ALSO, THE DRAIN LINES FROM THE REAR MANHOLE CONTAINMENT AREA WILL BE CONNECTED TOGETHER AND A VALVE INSERTED WHICH WILL BE CLOSED DURING TRANSPORTATION. THIS WOULD CONTAIN ANY MINOR SPILLAGE IN THE CONTAINMENT AREA AND PREVENT IT FROM ENTERING THE ROADWAY.

SOUTH CENTRAL POOL SUPPLY, INC. (SCP) DRIVER WAS STOPPED AT A RAILROAD CROSSING WHEN HIS VEHICLE WAS REAR-ENDED BY ANOTHER VEHICLE, WHICH WAS REAR-ENDED (3 CMV'S INVOLVED). EMERGENCY RESPONSE AUTHORITIES WERE SUMMONED TO THE SCENE, ALONG WITH LOCAL POLICE.  SCP ALSO HIRED A PRIVATE CONTRACTOR TO REMOVE THE DAMAGED PACKAGING CONTAINING THE HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION FROM THE SCENE AND DISPOSE OF IN ACCORDANCE WITH ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS (DISPOSAL PENDING AT THIS TIME).  THE SCP VEHICLE WAS PUSHED ONTO THE RAILROAD TRACKS AND LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONDERS, POLICE, ETC. CLOSED THE RAILROAD CROSSING AND THE INTERSECTION OF THE ACCIDENT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 4 HOURS WHILE STEPS WERE TAKEN TO SECURE THE AREA AND PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE FROM THE SCP VEHICLE (8 GALLONS TOTAL WERE DAMAGED AND POSED A PROBLEM WITH SPILLAGE).  THIS ACCIDENT WAS UNAVOIDABLE ON THE PART OF OUR DRIVER.

OUR DRIVER C. E. JONES WAS MAKING A PICK UP AT ALPINE ENGINEERED IN HAINES CITY, FL ON 5/12/97 AND WHILE THE SHIPPER WAS LOADING ON HIS TRAILER THE FORK LIFT OPERATOR RAN INTO THE PLT OF ORGANOPHOSPHORUS AND PUNCTURED 1 BAG.  OUR DRIVER THEN HELD THE BAG SHUT WHILE THE FORK LIFT PERSON GOT TAPE AND SEALED THE BAG.  OUR DRIVER WASHED HIS HANDS FOR A WHILE AND THEN WENT ON TO THE CONSIGNEE GOLD KIST. THEY TOLD HIM THEY COULD NOT ACCEPT IT AND HE CALLED INTO OUR OFFICE.  WE ADVISED OUR HOME OFFICE OF THIS AND THEY CALLED CLARK ENVIRONMENTAL CLEAN UP IN BARTOW, FL AND HAD THEM GO TO THE CONSIGNEE AND CONTAINED THE SPILL.  THEY PLACED INTO A 5 GAL PAIL WHAT LEAKED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND THEN PLACED THE TORN/TAPED BAG INSIDE A THICK PLASTIC BAG AND SEALED IT UP.  THE DRIVER THEN COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY AND BROUGHT BACK THE PAIL AND BAG  THE SHIPPER ADVISED US TO RETURN BOTH OF THEM IN GEORGIA WHICH WE DID ON 5/20/97.  WE FEEL THAT SOMETHING THIS HAZARDOUS SHOULD NOT BE SHIPPED IN BAGS ON AN OPEN PLT.  IT IS TOO EASY TO PUNCTURE A BAG.  SHOULD BE PUT IN A THICK BOX OR EVEN A CRATE FOR PROTECTION IN TRANSIT.

AT THIS TIME THE CLIENT WAS NOTIFIED AND A CREW WAS SENT TO ASSIST IN CLEANUP.  THE DRIVER WILL BE INSTRUCTED TO INSPECT DRUMS CLOSER AND A POSSIBLE RECOMMENDATION TO GENERATOR TO SWITCH TO CLOSED TOP POLY DRUMS.

column168: THE DRIVER OF THE POWER UNIT AND TRAILER LEFT HIDALGO SMELTER AND TRAVELED NORTH ABOUT 5 MILES, HE WENT AROUND A CORNER, THEN PASSED A CAR IN PROPER FASHION, RETURNED TO HIS SIDE OF THE ROADWAY AND WENT ABOUT 1 HALF A MILE, AT THIS POINT HE STARTED TOWARD THE BAR PIT AT A SLIGHT ANGLE, CONTINUED IN A STRAIGHT LINE THE WIDTH OF THE UNIT, CORRECTED THE DIRECTION OF TRAVEL BACK INTO THE ROADWAY AND AT THIS POINT OVERTURNED THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT.  THE UNIT AT THIS POINT WAS IN A JACKNIFE POSITION. THIS WHIPPED THE CAB OF THE POWER UNIT HARD AGAINST THE ROADWAY AND SPLIT THE CAB APART, ALSO WHEN THE TRACTOR UNIT CAME UP OUT OF THE BARPIT THE PASSENGER SIDE FUEL TANK SCRAPED THE PAVEMENT RUPTURING IT AND SETTING IT A FIRE, AS THE UNIT ROLLED AND SLID IT SPILLED FLAMING DIESEL ON THE ROAD AND CAB, AS IT CAME TO REST ON THE DRIVERS SIDE IN THE BAR PIT, THE FLAMING DIESEL CONTINUED TO POUR FROM THE PASSENGERS SIDE FUEL TANK ONTO THE GROUND AND IT IGNITED THE FUEL SPILLING FROM THE DRIVER SIDE FUEL TANK.  THE FUEL MELTED THE ALUMINUM FUEL TANK ON THE DRIVERS SIDE AND ENGULFED THE COMPLETE POWER UNIT IN FLAMES.  ALL COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS WERE CONSUMED BY THE FIRE.  THE DRIVER WAS CHARGED IN THE FIRE.

column168: THIS INCIDENT TOOK PLACE ON THE 19TH FRIDAY OF MAY 1997 AT ABOUT 9:15AM AT PERFECTION OIL CO. IN DUBUQUE, IA.  APPARENTLY OUR INSURED WAS CONTACTED BY PERFECTION OIL CO. TO DISPERSE 8,500 GALLONS OF UNLEADED FUEL INTO TWO TANKS WHICH COMBINED HOLD A TOTAL OF 30,000 GALLONS OF FUEL.  ACCORDING TO PERFECTION, THEIR RECORDS INDICATED THAT BETWEEN THE TWO TANKS THEY HAD 21,000 GALLONS ALREADY IN THEM AND SO THE ADDITIONAL 8,500 GALLONS WOULD BRING THEIR TANKS TO A CAPACITY OF 29,500 GALLONS.  HOWEVER ABOUT 40 MINUTES INTO OUR DRIVER UNLOADING HE NOTICED FUEL GATHERING AROUND HIS FEET.  HE THEN WENT AROUND TO THE OTHER SIDE OF HIS TRUCK AND FOUND THAT THERE WAS FUEL COMING OVER THE TOP OF ONE OF THE TANKS THAT HE WAS PUMPING INTO.  HE QUICKLY SHUT DOWN HIS UNIT AND ADVISED THE OFFICE PERSONNEL AT PERFECTION OIL CO.  THE PLANT MANAGER, JOHN KRITZ, GOT INTO HIS TRUCK AND DROVE AROUND BACK TO SEE IF THE VALVE TO THE STORM SEWER WAS SHUT AND WHEN HE JUMPED OUT OF HIS TRUCK HE RUPTURED THE TENDONS IN HIS LEG.  HE WAS ABLE TO HOBBLE DOWN TO SHUT OFF THE VALVE, HOWEVER HE COULD TELL THAT FUEL HAD GOTTEN INTO THE STORM DRAIN.  THE DUBUQUE CITY FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED TO FOAM DOWN THE AREA AND AMERICAN ENVIRONMENTALIST WERE CALLED IN TO FINISH CLEANING UP THE AREA.

column168: OFF-LOADING INTO STORAGE TANK AND TANK OVERFLOWED INTO CONTAINMENT AREA.  DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND RECEIVER HAD HIM WASH DOWN WITH WATER INTO DRAIN WHICH GOES INTO WATER TREATMENT TANK.  THIS OVERFLOW HAPPENED AT THE WATER TREATMENT PLANT FOR UNION CAMP.
RUPTURE DISC BLEW OUT.  TRAILER WAS PARKED HEAD UP HILL.  ABOUT 50 GALLONS RAN OUT INTO COLLECTION DRAIN.

DRIVER WAS STOPPED BY A STATE OF TEXAS DEPT OF PUBLIC SAFETY OFFICER FOR A TRAFFIC VIOLATION.  OFFICER OBSERVED A DRIP COMING FROM THE SIDE OF THE TANK TRAILER FROM A CRACK IN A WELD.  RESPONDING FOR CLEANUP WAS A SIX  (6) PERSON TEAM FROM RHONE POULENC CHEMICALS, INC. (THE SHIPPER) AND TWO (2) CARRIER TECHNICIAN LEVEL PERSONS.  THE SHIPPER PERSONS PERFORMED THE SPILL CLEANUP.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES. NOTE:  TRAILER HAD ORIGINALLY SHIPPED FROM RHONE POULENC TO ROLLINS ENVIRONMENTAL ON 4/4/97 - AND HAD BEEN RELEASED AS EMPTY ON 5/14/97 - DATE OF INCIDENT.  CARRIER WAS ENROUTE FROM DISPOSAL FACILITY TO CARRIER TERMINAL - PRESUMABLY EMPTY - WHEN THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED.

THE TRAILER FOR PST WAS BEING UNLOADED BY THE CONSIGNEE WHEN A FORK LIFT DRIVER PUNCTURED 1 DRUM WITH THE FORKS ON THE LIFT.  APPROXIMATELY 40 GALLONS OF MATERIAL LEAKED ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER.  THE SHIPPER (DOW CHEMICAL) SENT THEIR EMPLOYEES TO THE SITE TO DECONTAMINATE THE TRAILER.  APPROXIMATELY 12 FT BY 4 FT AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR HAD TO BE REPLACED.

column62: Abrasion; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: AFTER LOADING CARGO, DRIVER PROCEEDED TO TRUCKSTOP.  AT APPROXIMATELY 23:30 CDT TRI-STATE OPERATIONS DEPT. RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE UNION 76 TRUCKSTOP IN ALBUQUERQUE, NM ADVISING THEM THAT TRUCK 4371 HAD SOMETHING DRIPPING OUT OF THE TRAILER.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AS WELL AS THE SHIPPER WHO IN TURN RESPONDED WITH A RESPONSE CREW.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS REVEALED THAT A DRUM HAD A NAIL HOLE IN THE SIDE ABOUT 3 INCHES FROM THE BOTTOM.  THE DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR DECONTAMINATED BY MOTOROLA PERSONNEL.  LESS THAN FIVE GALLONS WAS SPILLED ON THE GROUND WHICH WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP BY MOTOROLA PERSONNEL UNDER DIRECTION OF THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: WHILE INSPECTING CARGO AT TERMINAL FACILITY IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM OF PAINT RELATED PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM AROUND THE BUNG AREA. APPROXIMATELY 2 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED INSIDE TRAILER.  SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED INSIDE TRAILER ON STEEL SECONDARY CONTAINMENT PAN.  CHEMICAL WASTE MANAGEMENT WAS CONTACTED WHO IN TURN SENT A RESPONSE CREW TO THE TERMINAL TO OVERPACK THE LEAKING CONTAINER. TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLEANED BY RESPONSE CREW WITH CLEANUP MATERIAL PLACED IN OVERPACK.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE IN TRANSIT FROM HOUSTON, TX TO MOBILE, AL ONE OF FOUR TOTE TANKS STARTED LEAKING SOME CORROSIVE MATERIAL INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE UNIT WAS DETAINED AT THE DOT SCALES AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT WAS NOTIFIED ALONG WITH OTHER AGENCIES.  THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS DETERMINED BY THE US COAST GUARD AS THE FILL CAP ON TOP OF THE TANK HAD NOT BEEN SECURED PROPERLY. THE MATERIAL SLOSHED IN TRANSIT UNTIL THE LID CAME OFF.  THE ACTUAL SHIPPER WAS WITCO CHEMICAL WHO HAD FILLED THE TOTE FOR JAMESTOWN CHEMICAL. THE CAUSE WAS OF HUMAN ERROR AND NOT PACKAGE FAILURE.

WHILE PICKING UP ADDITIONAL FREIGHT, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ONE DRUM WAS LEAKING SLIGHTLY FROM AROUND THE BUND.  SHIPPER TIGHTENED BUNG AND WIPED DRUM DOWN. ABSORBANT MATERIAL WAS PLACED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THIS WAS TAKEN ON TO DESTINATION WHERE IT WAS OFFLOADED BY CONSIGNEE.  NO FURTHER PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED.

column62: Derailment; Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: TRAIN M-BART3-22 DERAILED 19 CARS ON THE SOUTHERN EDGE OF MARTINEZ, CA.  BNSF STATION NAME OF GLEN FRAZER.  13 CARS CONTAINED HAZ MAT: 10 RESIDUE LPG , 2 PHOSPHORIC ACID AND 1 PAINT.  OF THE 10 RESIDUE LPG CARS, 5 OVERTURNED AND ROLLED DOWN AN EMBANKMENT ONTO RESIDENCE PROPERTIES.  THE CONTRA COSTA COUNTY FIRE CHIEF ORDERED A 1/4 MI RADIUS PRECAUTIONARY EVACUATION OF 35 RESIDENTS, WHICH BEGAN AT 1800 5/23, UNTIL LPG CARS COULD BE LOADED OUT OF THE AREA ON TRUCKS, THUS PERMITTING RECONSTRUCTION AND RESUMPTION OF SERVICE FROM ELECTRIC POWER LINES THAT WERE DESTROYED IN THE DERAILMENT.  RESIDENTS RETURNED AT 1800 5/24.  NO RELEASE OF HAZ MAT OCCURRED.  THE CAUSE OF THE DERAILMENT WAS DUE TO A STIFF  TRUCK BOLSTER THAT DID NOT SWIVEL ACCOUNT A CRACKED VERTICAL CENTER PLATE LINER THAT WAS CUTTING INTO THE CARBODY.  TRAIN ACCIDENT WAS REPORTED AS BNSF REPORT #NC-0597-107.

THIS TRAILER WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING DURING THE ROUTINE 1000 MILE INSPECTION.  BNSF RESPONDERS ASSESSED LOAD AND FOUND LADING HAD SHIFT CAUSING ONE DRUM TO LOSE ITS CAP AND RELEASE PRODUCT.  THE CAR WAS REMOVED FROM THE TRAIN, AND IT AND AN ADJACENT CAR WERE DECONTAMINATED.  THE LOAD WAS SENT TO THE ALBUQUERQUE RAMP TO BE RECONFIGURED   PRIOR TO FORWARDING TO DESTINATION.
column172: Drum - fiber, metal or plastic not specified

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: A YARD HOSTLER REPORTED AN ODOR WHEN DRAINING INTERMODAL UNITS IN THE VICINITY OF THIS AREA OF THE STORAGE YARD.  BNSF RESPONDERS DETERMINED ODOR TO BE RELEASING FROM THIS TANK CONTAINER.  THE BOTTOM BUTTERFLY OUTLET VALVE WAS OPEN AND THE OUTLET CAP WAS APPLIED LOOSELY.  THE VALVE WAS FULLY CLOSED AND THE OUTLET CAP WAS FULLY TIGHTENED. NO FURTHER ODOR PERSISTED.  NO LIQUID WAS RELEASED.

SWITCH CREW IN THE VICINITY OF THIS CAR REPORTED A FOUL STENCH. BNSF RESPONDERS IDENTIFIED THE CAR AND FOUND A FAILED SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THERE WAS NO PRESSURE IN THE CAR.  PRODUCT DID NOT RELEASE UNLESS THE CAR WAS MOVED.  CREWS WERE CAUTIONED TO AVOID THE AREA UNTIL THE CAR WAS TAKEN TO AN ISOLATED AREA OUTSIDE THE YARD.  THE SHIPPER MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR A REPLACEMENT SAFETY VALVE TO BE INSTALLED.  NO PRODUCT FELL TO THE GROUND.  AN ESTIMATED 1/2 GALLON WAS RELEASED ON THE CAR SIDES.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: DRIVER REPORTED THIS CONTAINER TO BE LEAKING PAINT-LIKE PRODUCT WHEN IT WAS IN THE STORAGE LOT AFTER DERAMPING FROM THE RAIL CAR.  BNSF RESPONDERS AND THE SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR ASSESSED THE LOAD AND NOTED ADEQUATE BLOCKING & BRACING WITH NO LOAD SHIFTING.  TWO LAYERS OF DRUMS ON PALLET WERE PRESENT.  ONE DRUM IN THE TOP LAYER LOST ONE PINT OF PRODUCT THROUGH A PIN HOLE NEAR THE TOP CHIME, BUT IN AN AREA OF AN INDENTION (LIKELY MADE BY A DRUM HANDLING DEVICE).  A SECOND DRUM IN THE FRONT STACK, LOWER LAYER HAD A FLAT SPOT IN THE SIDE WHICH BENT THE TOP ROLLING HOOP RESULTING IN A DISTRESS CRACK (PROBABLY WHILE IN TRANSIT).  ALL DRUMS WERE RECONDITIONED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS REMOVED, CLEANED AND RELOADED IN THE CONTAINER.  THE TWO LEAKING DRUMS WERE OVERPACKED.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: A ROLL-BY INSPECTION OF TRAIN H-HOGLI-20 REVEALED A LEAK FROM TANK CAR LOAD OF STYRENE MONOMER.  BNSF RESPONDERS COULD NOT STOP THE RELEASE BY TIGHTENING BOLTS SECURING THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE TO THE TANK CAR TANK FLANGE.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND CONTAINMENT FIXTURE PLACED TO CATCH DRIPPING PRODUCT.  THE SHIPPER'S CONTRACTOR RESPONDED AND WAS ABLE TO TIGHTEN THREE BOLTS ON THE FLANGE.  THIS STOPPED THE LEAK. THE CAR WAS HELD FOR OBSERVATION, THEN RELEASED TO DESTINATION. TRAIN DELAY TOTALED 7.0 HOURS ON 6 TRAINS.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: MANWAY DOME COVER IMPROPERLY SECURED, MONX 21808, MAY 22, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. PLAN WAS TO BY-PASS SENSOR AND FINISH FILLING THE TRUCK COMPARTMENT.  DRIVER SHOWED MECHANIC THAT COMPARTMENT TO BE FILLED WAS STILL EMPTY. ONCE DRIVER RESUMED LOADING, TRUCK COMPARTMENT OVERFLOWED.  THE SPILL WAS 106 GALLONS. MANAGEMENT IMMEDIATELY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. PRODUCT HAD BEEN CONTAINED ON THE LOADING RACK AND HAD BEEN WASHED DOWN INTO THE OILY WATER SYSTEM FOR RECOVERY.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER HAD CONNECTED THE LOADING ARM TO THE WRONG COMPARTMENT.  TO AVOID THIS FROM REOCCURRING, THE NEW POLICY STATES THAT TROUBLESHOOTING SHALL BE LED BY THE TERMINAL TECHNICIAN.  THEY WILL DETERMINE THE PROPER COURSE OF ACTION.  ANY REPAIRS MUST BE PERFORMED BY THE MECHANIC IN THE SHOP RELATIVE TO THE OVERFILL PROTECTION DEVICES.

column168: WHILE A 5,000 GALLON CARGO TANK WAS BEING FILLED WITH HYPOCHLORITE SOLUTION, THE DRIVERS SIDE LANDING GEAR LEG GAVE WAY TIPPING THE CARGO TANK OVER ON IT'S SIDE AND SPILLING APPROXIMATELY 2,322  GALLONS OF PRODUCT. ALL SUPPLY VALVES/PUMPS WERE IMMEDIATELY SECURED AND THE MANHOLE COVER ON TOP OF THE TANKER WAS CLOSED. THE AREA WAS FLUSHED WITH WATER FOR APPROXIMATELY FOUR HOURS. TO PREVENT A REOCCURRENCE, A PROCEDURE HAS BEEN IMPLEMENTED WHICH REQUIRED ANY TANKER/TRAILER BEING LOADED OR UNLOADED WITHOUT A POWER UNIT IN PLACE TO HAVE A STABILIZATION JACK IN PLACE.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DURING A YARD CHECK IT WAS NOTICED THAT A SUBSTANCE WAS SLIGHTLY LEAKING OUT OF THE REAR OF OUR TRAILER THAT WAS SPOTTED ON OUR RICHMOND YARD.  AFTER REVIEWING THE DOCUMENTS, WE CHECKED OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS BOOK AND ALSO OUR EMERGENCY GUIDE RESPONSE BOOK AND EVALUATED THE SITUATION AND NEUTRALIZED THE SPILLAGE WITH SODA ASH AND STA-DRY.  WE NOTIFIED BOTH THE SHIPPER AND RECEIVER.  WE HAD A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RECOVERY AND DISPOSAL COMPANY COME OUT ON SITE AND MADE SURE EVERYTHING WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP AND DISPOSED OF.  AFTER REVIEWING THE EVENT, WE DETERMINED THAT (1) ONE DRUM WHICH HAD WORKED ITSELF LOOSE FROM THE SHRINK WRAP HAD COME TO REST UP AGAINST THE NAILHEAD THAT WAS USED TO BRACE THE PALLET, THUS THE NAIL PUNCTURED A SMALL HOLE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, CAUSING IT TO LEAK.  WE HAVE DISCUSSED THE SITUATION WITH THE SHIPPER AND ARE CURRENTLY WORKING TOGETHER TO TAKE CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM RE-OCCURING IN THE FUTURE.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: LEAK WAS LOCATED AT THE THREADED NIPPLE AT BOTTOM OF THE TOTE WHERE THE VALVE SCREWS ON.  ALSO SIGN OF SPLASH OUT AT TOP OF THAT AND THREE OTHER TOTES DUE TO LOOSE DOME CAPS, SPLASH OUT WAS MINIMAL.  LEAK AT VALVE ONTO FLOOR OF TRAILER CAUSED THE FLOOR TO BECOME WET AND SLIPPERY.  THE 11 TOTES WERE LOADED DOWN THE CENTER SECURED BY 2' X 4' X 8 FOOT BOARDS ON EACH SIDE, WITH ONE NAIL AT EACH END. UPON EXAMINATION OF BOARDS AT SCENE, WAS FOUND THAT SOME NAILS BENT WHEN DRIVEN INTO TRAILER FLOOR AND WERE NOT FULLY INTO WOOD.  WITH SLICK FLOOR AS CONTRIBUTING FACTOR, WHEN DRIVER TURNED THE CORNER THE TOTES SLID, CAUSING TRAILER TO LEAN.  LEAK WAS CONTAINED ON PAVED PARKING LOT CLEANED UP AND DECONTAMINATED WITHOUT RELEASE TO ENVIRONMENT.  TO PREVENT IN FUTURE:POSSIBLY BETTER DESIGN OF RUBBER GASKETS, SECUREMENT CHECK, TIGHTENING OR MORE FREQUENT VALVE REPLACEMENT ON TOTES OF CORROSIVE MATTER

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Derailment
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 2345 HOURS, FRIDAY, MAY 30, 1997, CONTRAIL TRAIN ELSE-0 DERAILED THIRTY ONE (31) CARS, THREE OF WHICH CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, AT MILEPOST 229 OF THE CHICAGO LINE IN SCHUYLER, NEW YORK.  ALL APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  TANK CARS GATX 61310 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID, SOLUTION AND PPGX 3017 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION DERAILED BUT REMAINED INTACT WITH NO COMMODITY LOSS. TANK CAR GATX 61525 CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION DERAILED ON TO ITS SIDE ALLOWING A SMALL LEAK TO DEVELOP AT THE LIQUID LINE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 0200 HOURS,  MAY 31, 1997, SIXTY (60) HOMES WERE EVACUATED IN THE AREA. AT APPROXIMATELY 0345 HOURS MAY 31,  1997, EVACUATION CANCELED EXCEPT FOR TWO HOMES IN THE IMMEDIATE VICINITY. AT APPROXIMATELY 1700 HOURS, MAY 31, 1997, TANK CAR WAS UPRIGHTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE IMPACT OF THE DERAILMENT CAUSED TWO OF FOUR BOLTS ON THE LIQUID LINE VALVE TO LOOSEN. ESTIMATED RELEASE OF PRODUCT WAS DETERMINED TO BE 32 OUNCES.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 HOURS, MAY 31, 1997 THE TWO REMAINING FAMILIES WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN HOME. AN ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  ALL THREE CARS WERE TRANSPORTED TO WEST ALBANY, NEW YORK AND PRODUCT IN GATX 61325 WAS TRANSFERRED INTO GATX 61328.  CAR WILL BE LOADED ON A FLAT CAR AND RETURNED FOR HOME SHOP REPAIRS.

SWEEPINGS WERE ALSO PLACED IN DRUM. OVERPACK WAS LABELED AND SHIPPED.  AETS WILL WORK WITH CUSTOMER WHO PACKAGED DRUM TO ENSURE THAT DRUMS ARE NOT OVERFILLED IN THE FUTURE.

TRAILER VENT VALVE ACTUATOR CABLE SLIPPED THROUGH ITS ANCHOR BOLT WHEN THE VALVE HANDLE WAS OPERATED ALLOWING THE SPRING LOADED VALVE TO CLOSE AND THE CARGO TANK TO PRESSURIZE.  THE DOME LID HINGE BROKE AT ITS ATTACHMENT WELDS BEFORE THE INTERNAL CARGO TANK PRESSURE REACHED 28 PSIG RELEASING CRUDE OIL INTO THE AIR.  ACTION:  1) REPLACE 1/8" VENT VALVE CABLE WITH 3/16" STEEL AIRCRAFT CABLE TO HELP PREVENT CABLE SLIPPAGE.  2)  REPLACED DOME LID.  VISUALLY INSPECT SIMILAR DOME LIDS IN FLEET.  NOTIFY DOME LID MANUFACTURER OF INCIDENT.  NOTE:  NO OTHER DOME LID PROBLEMS HAVE BEEN DETECTED. 3)  CONTAMINATED SOIL HAS BEEN BIOREMEDIATED ON SITE.

column168: I WAS SOUTHBOUND ON METCALF AT 52ND STREET AT ABOUT 1 PM.  TRAFFIC WAS MOVING NORMALLY ON A CLEAR DAY.  I WAS CLIMBING METCALF HILL AT ABOUT 35 MPH IN THE CENTER LANE. WHEN ALL OF A SUDDEN THERE WAS THIS BIG CRASH.  WHEN I LOOKED IN THE MIRROR I SAW THIS RED CAR SPINNING OUT OF CONTROL.  AT THIS TIME I NOTICED GASOLINE FLOWING OUT OF MY TRAILER.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO GET TO A SAFE PLACE ON THE SIDE OF THE ROAD.  I CALLED DISPATCH  AND INFORMED THEM OF THE ACCIDENT.  I GOT OUT OF THE VEHICLE AND CHECKED ALL OF THE TRAILER OUT (LOOKING FOR LEAKING PRODUCT, PUNCTURES, AND SO FORTH).  I THEN WENT TO CHECK ON THE DRIVER OF THE OTHER VEHICLE TO SEE IF HE HAD BEEN INJURED.  AT THIS TIME HE CLIMBED OUT OF THE SUN ROOF OF HIS VEHICLE.  HE INFORMED ME HE WAS FINE.  HE THEN TOLD ME THAT HE WAS MOVING AT ABOUT 75 MPH WHEN HE TRIED TO PASS ME ON THE RIGHT.  HE SAID THAT HE LOST CONTROL OF HIS VEHICLE AND STRUCK MY TRAILER.

column168: DRIVER WAS INFORMED OF THE LEAK BY A PASSING MOTORIST.  OUR DRIVER OFF THE ROAD TO EVALUATE THE SITUATION.  HE CALLED MIKE PHARRIS (LOUISVILLE INORGANIC MATERIALS MANAGER) ABOUT 10:45 A.M. MIKE PHARRIS CONTACTED THE ELIZABETHTOWN POLICE DEPT AT APPROXIMATELY 11:00 A.M. AND WAS INFORMED THAT AN OFFICER WAS ARRIVING AT THE SCENE.  MR. MIKE HULSEY, BATTALION CHIEF OF THE ELIZABETHTOWN FIRE DEPT WAS THE EMERGENCY COORDINATOR AT THE SCENE.  AT 11:30 A.M., THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS DECIDED TO CLOSE THE ROAD, A NEARBY RAILROAD, AND THE EVACUATED SEVERAL NEARBY BUSINESSES.  A REQUEST WAS MADE FOR A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET.  OUR EVANSVILLE BRANCH FAXED ONE TO THEM.  AS REQUIRED MIKE PHARRIS REPORTED THE SPILL TO THE NATIONAL SPILL RESPONSE LINE (REPORTED TO MR. BRIGHT, #388516) AND TO THE KENTUCKY SPILL REPORTING LINE (MR A YOUNG, #971002).  MIKE CONTACTED JOE HOERTER AT OUR LOUISVILLE WAREHOUSE AND LOADED EMPTY BLEACH DRUMS, ABSORBENT, PUMP AND OTHER CLEAN UP MATERIALS ONTO OUR TRAILER. THEY LEFT FOR ELIZABETHTOWN ABOUT 2:00 P.M.  THEY ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AT 2:30 P.M.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS WERE EMPTYING THE MATERIAL FROM THE TOTE TO A CONTAINER THAT THEY OBTAINED FROM DOW CORNING.  THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT WAS COMPLETED AT 3:30 P.M.  THE SCENE WAS DECLARED "STABLE", THE AREA WAS REOPENED AND OUR PERSONNEL WAS ALLOWED TO COMPLETE THE CLEAN UP.  WE COMPLETED THE CLEAN UP ABOUT 5:30 P.M.  THE "CONTAMINATED" EQUIPMENT USED BY THE EMERGENCY RESPONDERS AS WELL AS SPILLED AND CONTAINMENT MATERIAL WAS PLACED INTO DRUMS AND TRANSFERRED TO OUR LOUISVILLE WAREHOUSE.  THE INTERIOR OF OUR TRAILER WAS CLEANED BY ALLWASTE CONTAINER SERVICES. WE LEFT THE SCENE.

THE PROBLEM IS THAT ONE GALLON INNER CONTAINERS ARE GREATLY EXCEED THE  AMOUNT OF MATERIAL ALLOWED UNDER THE EXCEPTED QUANTITY PROVISIONS.  THIS IS CONSIDERED A "REPORTABLE DISCREPANCY" UNDER THE PROVISIONS OF 49 CFR.  THE TAMPA FAA OFFICE WAS NOTIFIED AND THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD FOR FAA INSPECTION.

WHEN DOCK WORKER WAS UNLOADING TRAILER HE DISCOVERED THAT SOME OF THE MATERIAL IN THE TOTES HAD LEAKED AROUND THE CLOSURES ON TOP OF TOTES AND HAS RUN DOWN TOTE AND ON TO CARTONS FROM ANOTHER SHIPMENT WHICH WERE ON FLOOR OF TRAILER BETWEEN LEGS OF TOTES.  SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND MSDS WAS SECURED.  ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES WAS CALLED IN TO PUT NEW SEALS ON TOTES AND TO CLEAN UP SPILLAGE.  THIS WAS DONE AND TOTES WERE FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.  DISPOSITION OF CLEAN UP MATERIALS WILL BE HANDLED BY ENVIROMENTAL SERVICES.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE PAIL WAS DAMAGE WHEN HE UNLOADED THE FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  A SKID OF FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED ON TOP OF THE SKID CONTAINING THE PAILS.  DURING TRANSIT THE WEIGHT ON TOP OF THE PAILS CAUSED ONE OF THE PAILS TO BECOME CRUSHED ON THE TOP AND THE SIDE CAUSING SOME OF THE LIQUID INSIDE THE PAIL TO LEAK OUT. DAMAGED PAIL TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR FURTHER HANDLING. THE LOADING FACILITY WAS NOTIFIED OF THE DAMAGE WITH THE DOCK PERSONNEL WHO LOADED THE FREIGHT BEING COUNSELED ON THE PROPER WAY TO LOAD AND PROTECT PAILS FROM DAMAGE.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED THE DAMAGED BAG WHILE HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  THE LOADING FACILITY TO PLACE SHEETS OF SCRAP CARDBOARD BETWEEN THE ROUGH TRAILER WALL AND THE SKID OF BAGGED FREIGHT IN ORDER TO PREVENT IT FROM BEING TORN.  DAMAGED BAG WAS RECOUPED AND THE SPILLED GRANULAR MATERIAL WAS PLACED IN A CONTAINER FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIROMENTAL CONTRACTOR. CORRECTIVE ACTION TAKEN WITH THE DOCK MAN WHO LOADED THE SKID AT THE ORGIN FACILITY.

DOCK MAN DISCOVERED DAMAGE CARTON AS HE WAS UNLOADING FREIGHT FROM THE INBOUND TRAILER.  A SKID OF FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED AT THE ORGIN FACILITY AND HAD PUSHED AGAINST THE CARTON OF ADHESIVE CRUSHING IT.  THE PRESSURE CAUSED 9 OF THE 12 TUBES OF CAULKING ADHESIVE TO RUPTURE ON THE SIDE NEAR THE TOP RELEASING SOME OF THE MATERIAL.  CARTON TRANSFERRED TO OS&D FOR DISPOSAL BY AN ENVIORMENTAL CONTRACTOR. THE DOCK MAN RESPONSIBLE FOR LOADING THE FREIGHT AT THE ORGIN FACILITY RECEIVE CORRECTIVE ACTION ON HOW TO PROPERLY LOAD HAZARDOUS FREIGHT.

column168: BROKEN VALVE AT THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE, UTLX 46748, JUNE 9, 1997, ALBANY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1505 HOURS, MONDAY JUNE 9, 1997, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR AT CONRAILS FRONTIER YARD, BUFFALO, NY OBSERVED COMMODITY ON SIDE OF TANK CAR UTLX 46748 CONTAINING ETHANOL. APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, CONRAIL'S FRONTIER CAR SHOP MANAGER AND TERMINAL SUPERINTENDANT DETERMINED TANK CAR WAS LEAKING NEAR THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  AT APPROXIMATELY 1800 HOURS, THE BUFFALO HAZ MAT TEAM AND THE CHEEKTOWAGA FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT THE SITE. AT APPROXIMATELY 1815 HOURS, JUNE 9, 1997, REPRESENTATIVES FROM EPS, A CONTRACT ENVIRONMENTAL REMEDIATION COMPANY CALLED BY CONRAIL, ARRIVED AT THE SITE AND UPON EXAMINING THE CAR THEY DETERMINED THAT IT HAD A BROKEN VALVE AT THE SLIP TUBE GAUGING DEVICE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT CAR SHOULD BE OFF LOADED DUE TO THE EXPANSION OF THE COMMODITY AND BECAUSE OF THE FAULTY SLIP TUBE GAUGE. AT 2055 HOURS, EPS COMMENCED REDUCING SIX HUNDRED FIFTY (650) GALLONS OF COMMODITY FROM TANK CAR UTLX 46748 INTO THEIR VAC TRUCK. AT APPROXIMATELY 2105 HOURS, OFF-LOADING WAS COMPLETED. AT APPROXIMATELY 2200 HOURS, EPS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP THE SPILLED PRODUCT. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE SHIPPER PEKIN ENERGY ARRIVED, REPAIRED THE TANK CAR AND IT WAS THEN FORWARDED TO DESTINATION.

ON MAY 27, 1997 AT APPROXIMATELY 0745hrs A RAILROAD TANK CAR, SERIAL RCRX 1402, EMPTY LAST CONTAINING HYDROCHLORIC ACID,SOLUTION, WAS OBSERVED LEAKING (FUMING FROM THE TOP) WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT KCS' BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA CLASSIFICATION RAILYARD.  THE BATON ROUGE FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE INCIDENT AND DETERMINED THAT THREE (3) EDUCTION VALVE BOLTS WERE MISSING.  THE BATON ROUGE FIRE DEPARTMENT RE-INSTALLED THE THREE BOLTS AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE LEAK CONSISTED OF MINIMAL VAPOR FROM THE FUMING HYDROCHLORIC RESIDUE. column168: DURING THE OFFLOAD OF FEDEX FLIGHT 1952, TAIL NUMBER N127FE, WE CAME ACROSS THREE BOXES FROM THE SHIPPER. ALL THREE BOXES HAS BEEN COMPROMISED (RIPPED). THE FREIGHT HAD BEEN LOADED IN POSITION A1 IN THE BELLY OF THE AIRCRAFT. THE CONTENTS OF ONE OF THE BOXES DUMPED IT'S BATTERIES. UPON IMPACT WITH THE FLOOR OF THE AIRCRAFT, THE BATTERIES BEGAN SHOOTING SPARKS FROM THE SHORT CIRCUITING. THE BATTERIES WERE REMOVED FROM THE AIRCRAFT AND PLACED ASIDE IN THE WAREHOUSE. I CALLED THE SHIPPER AND SPOKE WITH A KENNETH SCOTT. MR. SCOTT WAS NOT COOPERATIVE. MR. SCOTT WAS MORE INTERESTED IN DETERMINED HOW THE BOX WAS COMPROMISED THAN IN SUPPLYING ME WITH A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA MSDS WOULD BE FORTHCOMING. I ALSO CALLED AND DISCUSSED THE MATTER WITH JOE HUMPHIES AT EXIDE. I THEN CALLED FAA SPECIAL AGENT JERRY SPERRO FROM THE CASFO. AGENT SPERRO WAS IN THE BUFFALO AREA AND HAS INSPECTED THE FREIGHT. I ADVISED HIM THAT FEDEX BELIEVES THAT THESE BATTERIES FALL UNDER THE AUSPICES OF 49CFR 173.21 AND ARE FORBIDDEN BY AIR. THE FREIGHT WILL BE HELD AT FEDEX UNTIL AGENT SPERRO ADVISES THAT THE RECIPIENT MAY RECOVER THE FREIGHT. THE MSDS FAXED BY THE SHIPPER CLEARLY INDICATES THE BATTERIES ARE DANGEROUS GOODS, UN2800. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

DURING A SORT THE BOX WAS FOUND TO BE GIVING OFF A STRONG ODOR. THE BOX WAS REMOVED FROM THE SORT AND OPENED. WE FOUND WHAT APPEARS TO BE A CARBURATOR OF FUEL CONTROL UNIT. APPROXIMATELY 30 ML OF WHAT WE BELIEVE TO BE JET A FUEL. THE ODOR SEEMED TO BE STRONGLY PETROLEUM-BASED. THE FREIGHT WAS HELD AND I CALLED THE FAA'S SOUTHWESTERN REGION DUTY OFFICER. I WAS CONNECTED WITH RAY WHITE. I EXPLAINED WHAT HAS OCCURED AND THAT WE WOULD HOLD THE FREIGHT PENDING AN FAA INSPECTION. THIS MORNING I SPOKE WITH STEVE BRASHER AND RELAYED THAT SPECIAL AGENT STEVE PEREZ WOULD BE COMING TO THE DFW RAMP TO INSPECT THE FREIGHT AT 0900 HRS ON 5/15/97. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS, LABELING, SHIPPING PAPERS OR OTHER INDICATORS TO LEAD US TO BELIEVE THE CONTENTS WERE REGULATED.

column168: PACKAGE WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE OCCURED. THE PACKAGE WAS APPARENTLY DROPPED IN HANDLING. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION OF THE SHIPPER FOR DISPOSITION.

THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING. UPON INSPECTION BY OUR DG/SPILL SPECIALIST IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE INNER CONTAINERS THAT WERE LABELED WITH FOUR CHEMICAL NAMES: TRICHLOROACETIC ACID 100 GRAMS, SODIUM PHOSPHATE 250 GRAMS, SODIUM PYROPHOSPHATE 100 GRAMS, AND SODIUM DODECYLSULPHATE (AMOUNT READABLE). SOME OF THE LIQUID THAT LEAKED WAS NOT IN LABELED INNER RECEPTACLES. ALSO ENCLOSED WERE PIPETTES AND EQUIPMENT USED IN DNA TESTING. I REQUESTED COPIES OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEETS (SEE ENCLOSED) FROM THE SHIPPER. ONE PRODUCT APPEARS TO BE UNDECLARED DANGEROUS GOODS SO I PHONE F.A.A. AGENT RAY MONTGOMERY AT (301) 215-2280. WE WILL HOLD THE SHIPMENT PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.

SHIPMENT WAS BEING HANDLED DURING THE OUTBOUND PACKAGE SORT WHEN THE DAMAGE WAS NOTICED. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED BY A FREIGHT FORWARDER IN THE MIAMI AREA, JET-EX. THIS SHIPMENT HAD BEEN REFUSED SEVERAL TIMES BEFORE JUST SIMPLY BEING LEFT BY SOMEONE ASSUMED TO BE WITH THE FREIGHT FORWARDER. THE SHIPMENT HAD BEEN DROPPED AND HAD BEEN LEAKING WHICH WAS THE INITIAL REASON FOR THE PREVIOUS REFUSALS. UPON CLOSER EXAMINATION IT WAS REVEALED THE PLASTIC INNER BOTTLE ACTUALLY CONTAINED ACETONE, AN EXTREMELY FLAMMABLE LIQUID. THERE WERE NO HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MARKINGS OR LABELS EXHIBITED ON THE OUTER PACKAGE NOR WAS THERE A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS IN EVIDENCE WITH THE SHIPMENT. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD PENDING NOTIFICATION TO THE F.A.A. FOR INVESTIGATION.

column168: UPRR SOUTHERN CORRIDOR MANAGER RON DAME REPORTED THAT TANK CAR TILX190023, ENTRAINED ON MHOFWB 01, WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP.  TRACK INSPECTOR TONY DELLENO NOTED THE LEAK WHILE WORKING.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  THE WACO FIRE DEPT. WAS ON SCENE COOLING THE VAPOR SPACE WITH WATER.  THEY STATED THAT WHEN THE CAR WAS COOLED, THE LEAKAGE STOPPED.  WHEN LEFT ALONE, PRODUCT RAN OUT OF THE MANWAY.  AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS 75 DEGREES.  THE MANWAY BOLTS WERE CHECKED AND TIGHTENED BUT THE CAR STILL LEAKED WHEN NOT COOLED.  CAR WAS OPENED UP AND PRODUCT WAS APPROXIMATELY 2" FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE RIM.  THE CAR WAS RESECURED AND WATER COOLING WAS CONTINUED UNTIL DUSK.  MARK WHITE, MUREX 972-702-0978, WAS CONTACTED VIA CHEMTREC AT 1600 HRS., DATE AND ADVISED OF INCIDENT.  HE WAS RECONTACTED WHEN CAUSE WAS FOUND AND DISPATCHED A TANK TRUCK, HAMNER TRUCKING, INC., TO LOCATION.  APPROXIMATELY 4,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS TAKEN OFF TILX190023.  THIS WAS APPROXIMATELY 20" OF OUTAGE. LOAD REDUCTION WAS COMPLETED AT 0250 HRS., 5-3-97.  CAR WAS SECURED, RESEALED, AND RELEASED.  REDUCED PRODUCT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

column168: ON 05-09-97 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:45PM MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER, RECEIVED A CALL FROM SENIOR MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY H. BART THAT AN HBT SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN SPLASHED WITH SULFURIC ACID FROM THIS CAR.  REEDER AND EMG MGR. DON JENKS RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND THE CAR SPRAYING ACID FROM THE EDUCTION PIPE.  THE WELD WHERE THE PIPE MEETS THE FLANGE AND FAILED, ALLOWING INTERNAL PRESSURE TO FORCE LIQUID UP THE PIPE AND THROUGH THE CRACK.  THE WEATHER WAS RAINY.  THE SWITCHMAN HAD BEEN WALKING TOWARD THE CAR AS THE LOCOMOTIVE WAS DRAGGNG THE CARS TOWARD HIM.  THE SWITCHMAN WAS SPRAYED ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF HIS HEAD.  THE LIQUID FELL ON HIS HAT, RIGHT EAR, NECK, AND DOWN ONTO HIS COLLAR.  HIS RAIN SLICKER PREVENTED SERIOUS INJURY.  HE WAS TAKEN BY AMBULANCE TO THE HOSPITAL FOR MEDICAL TREATMENT (INCIDENT #0597H0008) AND WAS RELEASED LATER THAT NIGHT.  A TEAM FROM LYONDELL RESPONDED AND WAS ABLE TO VENT THE PRESSURE FROM THE CAR, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE EDUCATION LINE WAS REPLACED AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO RETURN TO SERVICE. THE ACID THAT WAS SPILLED ON THE BALLAST WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH.

column168: MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY CLIFF HILL WAS NOTIFIED AT 1300 HRS, MAY 17TH THAT YMU55-17 HAD DERAILED ON CROSSING IN MUSKOGEE YARD, MP 503.25, ON CHEROKEE SUB.  HE WAS FURTHER ADVISED 5 CARS OF ANHYDROUS AMMONIA WERE INVOLVED AND THAT ONE CAR APPEARED TO BE LEAKING.  MGR. HILL ARRIVED AT DERAILMENT AT 1730 HRS.  HIS INSPECTION REVEALED TANK CAR ACFX 18625 WAS LEAKING FROM THE GAUGING DEVICE; HOWEVER REPAIRS COULD NOT BE MADE UNTIL CAR WAS UP-RIGHTED.  THE FOLLOWING EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED TO GAUGING DEVICE WHICH ALLOWED AMMONIA TO LEAK FROM CAR:  NEEDLE VALVE LOCATED ON TOP OF GAUGING ROD WAS ALL THE WAY OPEN ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK PAST VALVE, PACKING GLAND NUT WAS LOOSE ALSO ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  SECURED BOTH THE NUT AND VALVE WHICH SECURED LEAKING CAR.  NOTIFIED SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE STAN GOVELL WHO SAID HE WAS UNAWARE THERE WAS ANY PROBLEM WITH THE GAUGING DEVICE WHEN CAR WAS BEING LOADED.  MR. GOVELL WAS ADVISED THAT PROTECTIVE HOUSING COVER WAS SECURE AND SEALED AT TIME OF DERAILMENT.

CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WAS NOTIFIED BY BEN PEDERSEN, RISK MANAGMENT COMMAND CENTER, THAT A TANK CAR OF MTBE AT RODEO SIDING NEAR MP 25.5 ON THE MARTINEZ SUB-DIVISION, WAS LEAKING VAPOR.  INCIDENT WAS REPORTED BY A CONCERNED CITIZEN TO RODEO FIRE DEPARTMENT, WHO IN TURN NOTIFIED CONTRA COSTA COUNTY HEALTH, WHO THEN NOTIFIED UNION PACIFIC RAILROAD OF THE INCIDENT.  AGENCIES ON THE SCENE: CONTRA COSTA COUNTY HEALTH, UPRR POLICE, UPRR HAZMAT, TOSCO REFINING EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM, AND THE CITY OF RODEO FIRE DEPARTMENT.  ERNIE SIROTEK MADE ENTRY TO THE SUSPECTED LEAKER WITH CONTRA COSTA COUNTY HEALTH, AND DISCOVERED A VAPOR RELEASE FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  "O" RING REPLACED TO CORRECT THE CONDITION.  REPAIRS COMPLETED AT 1715 HRS AND CAR RELEASED TO DESTINATION.  THE FOLLOWING NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE: CAOES 97-19172, NRC 387530, AND CHEMTREC #54706.

column168: INTERLINE CARRIER MARITIME SERVICES ARRIVED AT SEA-LAND SERVICE, INC. GATE ENTRANCE.  TANK HAD STOPPED FOR GUARD TO LOG INTO OUR FACILITY.  OUR SECURITY GUARD, OFFICER MARTIN, WALKED AROUND THE BACK OF THE TANK NCTU028075 TO INSPECT FOR LEAKS.  HE NOTICED A SUBSTANCE ON THE FRAME OF THE DROP DECK CHASSIS.  THE OFFICER NOTIFIED SAFETY COORDINATOR PAT PARRISH.  PAT PARRISH OBTAINED PAPERWORK FROM THE DRIVER AND CONTACTED THE PORT OF HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ASSIST WITH OVERFLOW OF HAZARDOUS PRODUCT.  SEA-LAND GUARD REROUTED TRAFFIC TO SCALE 1 AND 2.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP AND HAD APPARENTLY STOPPED.  THIS WAS COMPLETED BY 3:00PM.  THE DRIVER ADVISED THERE WERE FOUR OTHER TANKS LEAVING THE SUPPLIER.  MS. PARRISH REQUESTED TO STOP THE TRUCKS EN ROUTE AND CHECK TO ENSURE THE TANKS WERE NOT OVERFLOWING AND LEAKING.

05/12/97 SORT SUPERVISOR TARA DUNN REPORTED A LEAKING SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR IN B BUILDING OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE AND HAZMAT SPILL TECHNICIAN DONNA RESOR RESPONDED TO THE SPILL.  UPON ARRIVAL, DONNA DONNED AN AIR PURIFIYING RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE SHIPMENT.  WE FOUND A BROWN FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE. THE LIQUID WAS PH'D, READING WAS NEUTRAL.  DONNA OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND 12 PLASTIC PUMP SPRAY BOTTLES OF "FLEA-B-GON" FLEA AND TICK KILLER. INFORMATION ON THE BOTTLES INDICATED THIS TO BE TOXIC TO MARINE LIFE. HAZMAT COORDINATOR FRAN VANCE MADE THE DECISION TO HOLD THE SHIPMENT FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED, PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND TAGGED TO BE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE SHIPMENT WAS RESEALED, PLACED INSIDE 2 PLASTIC BAGS AND TAGGED TO BE HELD FOR FAA INVESTIGATION.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PLACED IN THE HAZMAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.  THERE ARE NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO IDICATE THE CONTENTS ARE A REGULATED MATERIAL.  ONE OF THE INNER 12 BOTTLES LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 24 OUNCES.

THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY DECLARED, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED SHIPMENT OF RESIN SOLUTION.  IT WAS PACKED IN 1 X 5 GALON METAL CAN WITH A FRICTION (SCREW-TYPE) CLOSURE WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE.  IT APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE FRICTION (SCREW-TYPE) CLOSURE, FROM WHICH APPROXIMATELY .5 OUNCES OF PRODUCT LEAKED.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS REPACKED IN A D.O.T. column168: THIS WAS AN UNDECLARED SHIPMENT OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. ON MAY 26, 1997, SOUTHWEST AIRLINES FLIGHT 1474 ARRIVED IN SLC AT 1917. DURING DOWNLOADING OF THE AIRCRAFT EMPLOYEES SMELLED THE ODOR OF GASOLINE, A SEARCH OF THE BIN REVEALED THAT A NYLON BAG WAS LEAKING GASOLINE. OPENING THE BAG REVEALED AN OUTBOARD MOTOR. THE AIRCRAFT WAS COMPLETELY UNLOADED AND THE BIN WAS CLEANED AND AIRED. THE FLIGHT EXPERIENCED A DELAY OF 18 MINUTES DUE TO THE INCIDENT.

column42: AEROSOLS, NON-FLAMMABLE, (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column168: ON OPEATIONS DATE 5/1/97, I RECEIVED A CALL VIA RADIO THAT THERE WAS A PACKAGE LEAKING A WHITE SUBSTANCE IN SECONDARY "6" IN BUILDING "K" AT OUR SORT FACILITY, LOCATED AT 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO, 45177. UPON ARRIVAL TO THE LOCATION GIVEN THE PACKAGE IN QUESTION WAS QUICKLY IDENTIFIED AND PLACED IN A PLASTIC BAG. I THEN VISUALLY INSPECTED THE OUTSIDE PACKAGE AND ONLY FOUND THE AIRBORNE EXPRESS LIBRA LABEL AND NO OTHER MARKINGS OF ANY KIND. I THEN OPENED THE PACKAGE TO SEE WHAT WAS LEAKING AND FOUND ONE AEROSOL CAN, SEVERAL WHITE CLEANING RAGS ALL WRAPPED IN PACKING PAPER. FURTHER INSPECTION OF THE AEROSOL CAN REVEALED THAT THE ENTIRE CONTENTS HAD BEEN DISPERSED DUE TO THE PLASTIC CAP HAD NOT BEEN SECURED BY POSITIVE MEANS. THE AEROSOL CAN CONTAINED A METAL CLEANER, SO THE CLEAN UP OF THE STEEL SLIDE WAS EASY. THE PACKAGE WAS THEN TAKEN TO OUR HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AGENTS SORT BUILDING AND PLACED IN OUR SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL THE FAA HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AGENTS COULD INVESTIGATE IT. UPON RELEASE BY THE FAA THE SHIPMENT WILL BE RETURNED OR FORWARDED ACCORDING TO ALL APPLICABLE REGULATIONS SET FORTH BY TITLE 49CFR. NOTE: PACKAGE DIMINSIONS 8.5" X 12.25" X12.25" THIS MAY HAVE ATTRIBUTED TO THE AEROSOL LEAKING SINCE THERE WASN'T ANY MEANS TO SECURE THE AEROSOL CAN IN PLACE INSIDE OF THE PACKAGE, ALLOWING THE CAN TO SHIFT FREELY INSIDE.

column168: TWO DRIVER/SALESMEN WERE UNLOADING TRAILER 15-9683 FROM MILWAUKEE APPROX 0730 HRS . APPROXIMATELY 1/3 WAY INTO TRAILER, THEY NOTICED A SMELL AND SAW LIQUID WHICH HAD LEAKED FROM A TOTE.  AT THAT TIME, THEY STOPPED WORKING & REPORTED INCIDENT TO JOHN MCGOWN, TERMINAL MGR.  KEN HEIS, SALES EXEC CALLED CALGON & SPOKE WITH BRIAN LAPLANT, WHO INSTRUCTED KEN TO CALL THE HAZ MAT RESPONSE TEAM & THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT.  HAZ MAT TEAM ARRIVED AND EVACUATED THE BUILDING APPROX 0830 HRS.  A COMPLETE ON SITE INSPECTION WAS DONE & DETERMINED THAT FAIULRE OF THE FILL CAP WAS THE CAUSE. THE TWO DRIVERS THAT DISCOVERED THE SPILL WERE INSTRUCTED TO DISPOSE OF THEIR SHOES DUE TO CONTAMINATION, WHICH WAS DONE.  AREA WAS THEN DECLARED SAFE.  THEN CONTACTED DOUG MEINHARDT OF CENTRAL WISCONSIN ENGINEERS CLEAN UP CREW WHO ASSESSED THE LEAKAGE & DETERMINED THAT THERE WAS NO FURTHER HAZARD AS ONCE PRODUCT DRIES & EVAPORATES THERE IS NO FURTHER DANGER.  DAVE MARTIN OF CALGON FLEW TO THE TERMINAL ON MON, 5/12/97, AND RECAPPED THE TOTE.
TRAILER DOOR WAS NOT LATCHED PROPERLY AND A PAIL FELL ONTO HIGHWAY AND BURST OPEN.  LOCAL FIRE DEPT CLEANED UP SPILL AND PUT ALL INTO A RECOVERY CONTAINER.

THIS PACKAGE WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  UPON INSPECTION BY OUR DG/SPILL CLEANUP SPECIALIST, THE PACKAGE APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED THROUGH THE CAP. AFTER SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES WERE FOLLOWED, IT WAS CONTAINED SAFELY IN THE SALVAGE DRUM.  I CONTACTED THE SHIPPER TO OBTAIN THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET (MSDS), WHICH IS ENCLOSED.  THE SHIPMENT APPEARS TO BE BOTH CORROSIVE AND TOXIC ACCORDING TO THIS DOCUMENTATION. SINCE THE SHIPMENT WAS NOT SHIPPED AS DANGEROUS GOODS, I THEN PHONED STEVE BRASCHER, FAA AND LEFT A MESSAGE ON HIS VOICE MAIL.  HE PHONED BACK ON MONDAY AND SAID THAT HE WOULD BE GOING TO THE FEDEX FACILITY TO INVESTIGATE. THE SHIPMENT WILL BE HELD AT THE FACILITY PENDING THE FAA INVESTIGATION.

THE CAN WAS IN THE BOX SIDEWAYS.  IT WAS AGAINST ORIENTATION ARROWS.  WEIGHT OF LOAD CAUSED LID TO POP OFF BECAUSE IT WAS LAYING ON ITS SIDE.  ALSO WORE PROPER PPE, FOLLOWED DECISION TREE, USED FLAMMABLE LIQUID RESPONSE SHEET, ABSORBED WITH CLAY BASE ABSORBENT, ABSORBED ODOR WITH SOLUSORB, PROCESSED ENTIRE PACKAGE THROUGH DMP.

ON 5/28/97 A SHIPMENT OF 18/15 GALLON CONTAINERS OF ACID LEFT OUR DOCK VIA COMMON CARRIER (SILVER EAGLE) ENROUTE TO JEF CONSTRUCTION SUPPLY IN PORTLAND OR.  THE SHIPMENT LEFT OUR DOCK IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPLICABLE REGULATIONS AND COMPANY POLICY, AND WAS SIGNED FOR BY THE CARRIER.  THE FOLLOWING MORNING 5/29/97 AT APPROX, 0840 HRS, I RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE PORTLAND SILVER EAGLE TERMINAL, INFORMING ME THAT THERE WERE APPROX. 5 LEAKING CARBOYS OF ACID GIVING OFF VAPOR AND LEAKING.  THE LEAKERS HAD BEEN ISOLATED AND A LOCAL PRIVATE HAZ MAT FIRM HAD BEEN CALLED IN TO ASSESS THE SITUATION.  I THEN CONTACTED THE PROPER CHAIN OF COMMAND, AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT WE WOULD DISPATCH LARRY RAPP FROM OUT KALAMA, WA. PLANT TO CLEAN UP AND REPLACE THE BUNGS IN THE LEAKERS.  LARRY RAPP DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE 4 LEAKING BUNGS CAUSING THE SPILLAGE OF LESS THANK 1/4 GALLON TOTAL OF WHICH NO PRODUCT SPILLED TO THE GROUND OR SURROUNDING ENVIRONMENT.  HE THEN REPLACED THE LEAKING BUNGS, CLEANED UP THE REMAINING LEAKAGE AND THE SHIPMENT WAS COMPLETED BY THE CARRIER. LARRY RAPP ALSO OBSERVED WHAT APPEARED TO BE WOOD SHAVINGS AND SPLINTERS ON AND AROUND THE CARBOYS, POSSIBLY FORM THE STACKING OF OTHER FREIGHT ON TOP OF THE CARBOYS BY THE CARRIER, CONTRIBUTING TO THE SITUATION.

column42: ACETIC ACID SOLUTION, NOT LESS THAN 50 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 80 PERCENT ACID, BY MASS
column168: I WAS WORKING LOCAL SORT, WHEN AT APPROXIMATELY 16:20 P.M., MY SUPERVISOR GEORGE PAULISON ASKED ME TO GO MEET A DRIVER, MIKE TOCCP BECAUSE HE HAD A SPILL IN HIS TRUCK WHICH HAD A STRONG ODOR.  I LOADED UP THE SCBA AND ALL PROPER PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT NEEDED FOR A SPILL.  I WENT TO THE AREA WHERE THE DRIVER WAS AND HE TOLD ME IT SMELLED LIKE VINEGAR, BUT MUCH STRONGER.  I DONNED THE BOOTS, GLOVES, APRON, GOGGLES, AND ETC., INCLUDING THE SCBA AND PULLED THE UNMARKED LEAKING PACKAGE OUT OF THE PACKAGE CAR AND NOTICED IT HAD NO HAZARDOUS LABELS OR FIVE PART FORM ON IT.  I THEN PROCEEDED TO OPEN THE PACKAGE AND FOUND TWO CONTAINERS LABELED "CORROSIVE".  I THEN MADE SURE THAT THE DRIVER OR ANYONE ELSE DID NOT COME IN CONTACT WITH THE HAZARDOUS LIQUID, WHICH THEY DID NOT.  I THEN USED THE FLOOR ABSORBENT, WHICH I HAD TWO BINS OF, TO KEEP THE LIQUID FROM SPREADING ANYMORE THAN IT ALREADY HAD IN THE TRUCK. I PUT THE LEAKING PACKAGES, AND ANY OTHER WHICH CAME IN CONTACT WITH THE LIQUID IN THE PROPER BAGS FILLED WITH THE PROPER ABSORBENT MATERIAL, PUT THEM IN THE PLASTIC BINS, AND TAPED THE TOPS OF THE BAGS.  I THEN CLEANED UP THE INSIDE OF THE TRUCK WITH THE ABSORBENT AND INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO LEAVE THE DOORS OPEN TO AIR OUT THE TRUCK DUE TO THE STRONG ODOR AND CAME BACK TO THE BUILDING WITH THE LEAKING MATERIAL.

AT MIDNIGHT ON SUNDAY THE FOURTH OF MAY,  MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, HARRY W. RODABOUGH WAS NOTIFIED BY THE MTO AT SALT LAKE CITY, UT, REGARDING A DIESEL FUEL LEAK FROM TANK CAR UP70163.  HE WAS ADVISED THAT THE CAR HAD BEEN LEAKING FOR SOME TIME THAT THEY HAD ATTEMPTED TO NOTIFY HIM ONE WEEK EARLIER, BUT HAD FAILED TO MAKE CANTACT.  RODABOUGH RESPONDED TO THE YARD AND FOUND THE TANKCAR LEAKING WITH EVIDENCE OF A MAJOR SPILL. FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE CAR HAD A BAD ODOR NOTICE ATTACHED, DATED 9:00 A.M. 4/13/1997 FROM MR. RUDY SANCHEZ AT AMAVISUALCO OIL, INDICATING THE CAR HAD A CRACKED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE, AND THAT THE TANK WAS NOT SECURED TO THE UNDER FRAME OF THE CAR.  VISUAL INSPECTION DISCLOSED THAT THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE HAD BEEN SHEERED OFF, AND ONE OF THE  STRAPS THAT TIE THE TANK TO THE UNDER FRAME WAS BROKEN AND HAD BEEN SECURED IN PLACE WITH A BUNGEE CORD TO PREVENT A SAFETY HAZARD.  ALL THE BOLTS THAT SECURE THE TANK ONTO THE UNDER FRAME HAD BEEN SHEERED OFF, AND THE TANK WAS FOUND TO HAVE TWO HOLES IN THE BOTTOM ADJACENT TO THE OUTLET VALVE,  APPROXIMATELY THE SIZE OF DIMES.  MR. RODABOUGH OPENED THE CAR  TO CHECK THE LOAD AND FOUND THERE WAS ONLY ONE OR TWO GALLONS LEFT IN THE CAR.  THE STATE OF UTAH DEQ WAS NOTIFIED AS WELL AS CHEMTREC, MR. LEIF ERICKSON,  WAS FURNISHED WITH DETAILS AND ASSIGNED CASE NUMBER 54271.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: ON MONDAY, 052697 1106 HRS. SPECIAL AGENT HAZMAT, JERRY MEZA WAS NOTIFIED ABOUT TOFC, REDZ 233423 WHICH WAS LEAKING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. HE RESPONDED AND FOUND THAT THE TRAILER WAS LEAKING IN TWO DIFFERENT AREAS, AT THE MIDDLE AND BY THE REAR DOORS. IT APPEARED THAT ABOUT 1 GALLON OF PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE TWO DIFFERENT LOCATIONS. THE PRODUCT A REDDISH, MAROON IN COLOR MATERIAL WAS NOTED. HE FIELD TESTED THE PRODUCT ON PH PAPER AND OBTAINED AN IMMEDIATE READING OF > 11 READING. THIS FIELD TEST INDICATED THAT MEZA WAS DEALING WITH A CORROSIVE. HE IMMEDIATELY ISOLATED THE TRAILER TO A SAFE LOCATION NEARBY AND PLACED IT ON PLASTIC SHEETING. HE MADE ENTRY AND FOUND 72 DRUMS PLACARDER CORROSIVES, UN 3266 AND TOWARDS THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER NOTICED THREE DIFFERENT AREAS OF PRODUCT ON THE FLOOR. A CONTRACTOR CODE #3 INC. WAS CALLED OUT TO INCIDENT TO ASSIST WITH THE SPILL. THEY LOCATED ONE DRUM TOWARDS THE MIDDLE OF THE TRAILER AND PLACED IT INTO A POLY-OVERPACK. THEY FOUND THAT THE DRUM #19 LOT #22681 UN1A1/Y1.8/250 97/USA/NCCC. HAD A PUNCTURE AT THE BASE OF THE DRUM, BY THE RIM. THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA WAS CLEANED WITH SAND, WATER, & PICKED UP WITH ABSORBANT PADS. THE MAJORITY OF THE DRUMS WERE PHYSICALLY HANDLED AND INSPECTED FOR LEAKS. IT WAS ONLY DRUM #19 THAT SHOWED TO BE LEAKING. THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS ALSO PICKED UP AND THE REMAINING PPE AND PLASTIC DEBRIS WAS PLACED IN ONE POLY OVERPACK TO BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDINGLY BY THE CONTRACTOR. THE TRAILER WAS RELEASED 052797 ABOUT 0100 HRS. NOTIFICATION: RMCC:NOTIFIED APPROPRIATE REGULATORY AGENCIES. CHEMTRC:DEBRAM, J. NOTIFIED 052797 1228 HRS. ASHLAND CHEMICAL: ROBERT, ERICK NOTIFIED 052797 1440 HRS. AND AUTHORIZED THE CLEAN UP BY CODE # 3 iNC.

column168: AT 1455 HOURS ON 5/16/97, SR SPECIAL AGENT HAZ MAT T. J. BOUDREAUX RECEIVED A CALL FROM AVONDALE IMS MR BILL MAAS WHO ADVISED THAT ISO TANK CONTAINER OCLU 755107 WAS LEAKING PRODUCT, ETHANOL, FROM THE TOP.  MAAS WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE AND CONTACTED TRACY WHO REPORTED CASE UNDER INCIDENT #972119.  HE ALSO CONTACTED THE 911 EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER.  AT 1545 HRS BOUDREAUX ARRIVED IN THE IMS AVONDALE LOT PAD C WHERE ISO TANK CONTAINER OCLU 755107 HAD BEEN ISOLATED. PRODUCT COULD BE SEEN LEAKIGN DOWN THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TANK COMING FROM THE SPILL BOX. ON THE SCENE WAS IMS MGR MAAS AND THE AVONDALE VOLUNTEER FIRE COMPANY. BOUDREAUX INSPECTED THE FITTINGS/VALVES.  HE REMOVED CABLE SEAL HW 1009028 ON THE SPILL BOX COVER.  IT WAS NOTED THAT PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE BASE OF THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE VALVE WAS LOOSE AND COULD BE MOVED BY HAND.  AFTER CONTACTING CHARLIE WRIGHT 7 HERBY BART, BOUDREAUX SECURED A STRAP WRENCH AND TIGHENTED THE VALVE, WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE THE ISO TANK WAS IMPROPERLY PLACARDED. TWO PLACARDS HAD WHITE CENTER PANELS WITH NO UN NUMBER APPLIED & TWO PLACARDS INDICATED  FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND NO PANEL FOR UN NUMBER.  AT ABOUT 1700 HRS LOUISIANA STATE POLICE TROOPER, RONNIE MAYEAUX ARRIVE AND IT WAS DETERMINE THAT THE ISO TANK HAD BEEN OVERLOADED AND DUE TO THE WARM TEMPERATURE THE PRODUCT EXPANDED AND ESCAPED PAST THE LOOSE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  KAREN DICKENS P & O CONTAINER IN HOUSTON, TX WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED THAT APPROXIMATELY 100 GALS OF PRODUCT WOULD HAVE TO BE UNLOADED BY A CONTRACTOR TO MAKE LOAD SAFE FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  IT WAS RECOMMENDED THAT GULF STATE ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES BE CONTACTED TO PERFORM THIS SERVICE.  GULF STATES STEVE MUTZ WAS CONTACTED AND LATER ARRIVED WITH A CREW.  GULF STATES CREW REMOVED THE SEAL ON THE UNLOADING VALVE AND GRAVITY LOADED 2/58 GAL STEEL OVER PACK DRUMS THAT WERE LINED WITH POLYETHYLENE BAGS.  THE CREW ALSO CHECKED AND REPLACED THE GASKETS ON THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE 2/58 GAL DRUMS WERE THEN PLACED ON THE SP AVONDALE DOCK FOR AUTHORITY TO TRANSPORT THEM ON TO FINAL DESTINATION, FT SMITH, AR FROM P & O CONTAINER. BOUDERE UX APPLIED SEAL UNION PACIFIC F-482401 TO THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE AND SEAL UNION PACIFIC F-482402 TO THE COVER OF THE SPILL BOX.  TWO PLACARDS WERE REPLACED ON RIGHT SIDE OF REAR WITH UN NUMBER 1170 AND UN1170 WAS SCRIBED IN WHITE PANEL OF EXISTING PLACARDS ON THE LEFT SIDE AND FRONT OF THE TANK.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT 1820 HRS. ON 05/23/97, SR. SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAUX RECEIVED NOTIFICATION FROM IMS CLERK DIANA BARRIOS THAT ISO TANK UTCU 461207 WAS LEAKING ON PAD B OF THE AVONDALE, LA. IMS LOT. BARRIOS ADVISED THAT THE JEFFERSON PARISH, AVONDALE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON THE SCENE ALREADY. AT 1830 HRS. BOUDREAUX ARRIVED ON THE SCENE AND NOTICED A PUDDLE OF CLEAR LIQUID UNDER THE FRONT OF THE TANK. AT ABOUT 1845 HRS. WESTWEGO VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPT. HAZ MAT TECH. KENNETH BOUVIER ARRIVED. IT WAS DECIDED TO RETRIEVE A SAMPLE OF THE CLEAR LIQUID AND TEST ITS ACIDITY WITH A DEVICE THAT BOUVIER HAD. A FIREMAN WITH PROTECTIVE CLOTHING RETRIEVED THE SAMPLE WHICH TESTED 8.0 ON THE GAUGE WHICH PROVED THERE WAS ONLY A MINOR TRACE OF THE PRODUCE IN WATER. AN INSPECTION OF THE TOP OF THE TANK PROVED THAT A SEAM ON THE INSULATION JACKET HAD COME OPEN AND ALLOWED RECENT HEAVY RAIN TO ENTER BETWEEN THE JACKET AND THE TANK AND DRIP OUT THE BOTTOM. A CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE MANWAY COVER INDICATED THAT THE MANWAY COVER BOLTS MAY HAVE BEEN LOOSE DUE TO THE FACT THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE PRODUCT HAD FORCED ITS WAY UNDER THE COVER AND DRIPPED DOWN THE NECK OF THE MANWAY AND ONTO THE TOP OF THE TANK. NONE OF THE PRODUCT ESCAPED FROM THE SPILL BOX. EIGHT OF EIGHT MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH WHICH SECURED THE LEAK. THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE HAZ MAT CENTER IN BATON ROUGE WAS NOTIFIED AND CRYSTAL REPORTED INCIDENT UNDER #972247 AT ABOUT 1900 HRS. ON 05/23/97. AT 1930 HRS. BOUDREAUX ADVISED CRYSTAL OF THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE THAT THE SCENE WAS SECURED.

column168: AT 1735 HRS ON 5/12/97, SR SPECIAL AGENT HAZ MAT T. J. BOUDREAX RECEIVED A CALL FROM MYIO HILLARY LEVINER WHO ADVISED THAT A SWITCH CREW, WHILE SWITCHING SPINE CAR TTAX 76537 WITH ISO TANK CONTAINER NRSU 321168, NOTICED THAT A LIQUID PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING OUT OF THE TOP.  THE PRODUCT WAS TURPENTINE AND WAS LOCATED IN TRACK #133 IN THE SP AVONDALE YARD. THERE WERE NO INJUIRES INVOLVED WITH THIS INCIDENT.  LEVINER WAS INSTRUCTED TO NOTIFY THE LOUISIANA STATE POLICE WHICH HE DID AND MADE CONTACT WITH TRACY WHO ASSIGNED INCIDENT #972032 TO THIS CAUSE.  LEVINER ALSO NOTIFIED THE 911 JEFFERSON PARISH EMERGENCY RESPONSE CENTER.  UPON ARRIVAL, BOUDREAUX LOCATED THE ISO TANK CONTAINER AND MET WITH THE AVONDALE VOLUNTEER FIRE COMPANY.  AN INSPECTION OF THE ISO TANK REVEALED THE FOLLOWING: THE SPILL BOX COVER AT THE MANWAY WAS OPEN; THE MANWAY COVER SEAL CCIB 8 1073 WAS BROKEN; 8 OF 8 MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE LOOSE AND LAYING DOWN; 4 0F 4 NUTS ON THE BOLTS ON THE AIR VALVE DEAD END FLANGE WERE OFF AND LAYING INSIDE THE SPILL BOX; 3 OF 4 BOLTS WERE LOOSE ON THE LIQUID VALVE DEAD END FLANGE AND 1 BOLT AND NUT WERE LAYING INSIDE THE SPILL BOX; 4 0F 4 BOLTS ON THE ONLOADING VALVE DEAD END FLANGE WERE LOOSE WITH INTACT SEAL SINOTRANS SHAI 1249662 ON VALVE.  JEFFERSON PARISH SHERIFF'S OFFICE DEPUTY ROBERT COCHRAN ARRIVED AND REPORTED INCIDENT UNDER JPSO ITEM E-12132-97.  IT IS UNKNOWN AS TO WHAT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS LOST OR WHERE THE OPENING OF THE ISO CONTAINER OCCURRED.  ANY PRODUCT THAT ESCAPED IN THE AVONDALE YARD DISIPATED RAPIDLY.  THE 8 OF 8 MANWAY COVER BOLTS WERE APPLIED PROPERLY AND TIGHTENED DOWN BY HAND.  THE 12 BOLTS ON THE 3 DEAD END FLANGES WERE APPLIED AND TIGHENED DOWN WITH WRENCHES.  THE FOLLOWING SEALS WERE APPLIED:  UNION PACIFIC F-482255 TO THE MANWAY COVER; UNION PACIFIC F-482256 TO THE MANWAY SPILL BOX COVER; UNION PACIFIC F-482257 TO THE CALVES SPILL BOX COVER. CHEMTREC JEFF BOTWINICK WAS CONTACTED FOR SHIPPER NOTIFICATION AND A COPY OF MSDS FOR TURPENTINE. CHRIS DIMITRUCK OF THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE FINDINGS AND ACTIONS TAKEN.

column168: ON 053097 MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL SITE REMEDIATION, GEOFFREY REEDER RECEIVED A CALL FROM THE TRAIN CREW THAT THIS CAR WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP. UPON ARRIVAL, REEDER NOTICED A BLACK LIQUID RUNNING DOWN BOTH SIDES OF THE CAR. THE LIQUID WAS COMING FROM THE PLUG IN THE LIQUID EDUCTION LINE. REEDER RELIEVED THE PRESSURE USING THE AIR VALVE LOCATED ON THE SAFETY VENT PIPE. THIS MADE THE LEAK STOP. REEDER THEN NOTIFIED CHEMTREC AND ASKED THAT THE SHIPPER BE CONTACTED. INSTEAD, THE CONSIGNEE RESPONDED. THE CAR WAS WASHED AND THE SPILL NEUTRALIZED USING SODA ASH. TEFLON TAPE WAS APPLIED TO THE LIQUID PLUG TO PREVENT FURTHER LEAKAGE. THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED FOR NORMAL MOVEMENT.

ORIGINAL VALVE: MIDLAND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE MODEL # A-1779-NJBP-1A, SERIAL #GS57. NEW VALVE: MIDLAND SAFETY RELIEF VALVE MODEL #A-1779-NJBP-VA, SERIAL #MA750. THERE WERE NO DRAINS OR WATERWAY AFFECTED AS A RESULT OF THIS RELEASE, NOR DID ANY PRODUCT COME IN CONTACT WITH THE GROUND. column168: MGR. CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, RICK SLOANE RECEIVED CALL FROM "MARK" AT THE ALBINA RAMP CONCERNING LEAKING TANK CONTAINER MTLU 441500. MARK EXPLAINED THE CONTAINER WOULD LEAK FROM THE BOTTOM WHEN PLACED ON A CHASSIS. THE LEAKING MATERIAL WAS CREATING CLOUDS OF BLUE SMOKE WHEN IN CONTACT WITH RAINWATER PUDDLES. MGR. SLOANE INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND DETERMINED THE MATERIAL (DIMETHYL THIOPHOSPHORYL CHLORIDE) HAD CORRODED THROUGH THE TANK  AT THE BOTTOM REQUIRING TRANSFER. MR. SLOANE CONTACTED THE MANUFACTURER OF THE PRODUCT (ZENECA IND. LTD) AND ARRANGED FOR THEM TO HIRE A FIRM (MONGOMERY TANK LINES) TO TRANSFER THE IM TANK AND A CONTRACTOR (SMITH-RIDE) TO CLEAN UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL. WHILE WAITING FOR THE ARRIVAL OF THE TRANSFER EQUIPMENT AND THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR. MGR. SLOANE USED SODA ASH AND FIVE YARDS OF SAND TO STABILIZE THE RELEASE.

column168: ON SATURDAY, MAY 17, AT 7:00 A.M., OUR TRUCK ARRIVED AT CONDOR DRILLING FLUIDS, INC. IN DERBY ACRES TO BE NEUTRALIZED.  JIM WATSON, PLANT OPERATOR AT CONDOR, SAID THAT THEY WERE OUT OF CAUSTIC SODA AND ASKED THE DRIVER TO DRIVE TO ANOTHER CONDOR YARD LOCATED IN TAFT WHERE LIME WAS USED TO REACH A PH OF 2.5.  AFTER LEAVING THE CONDOR YARD IN TAFT WITH THE NEUTRALIZED LOAD, THE DRIER TURNED DOWN WOOD STREET TO DELIVER PAPERWORK TO HIS DISPATCHER'S HOUSE AND NOTICED FLUID LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF THE TANK.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY STOPPED HIS TRUCK, GENERATED A VACUUM ON HIS TANK, AND STOPPED THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER THEN CALLED THE DISPATCHER ON CALL, TOM SIMMS, AND TOLD HIM THAT HE HAD DEVELOPED A LEAK IN HIS TANK, STOPPED IT, AND ASKED WHAT TO DO NEXT.  THE DRIVER NEGLECTED TO RELATE TO TOM WHERE, HOW MUCH, AND WHAT WAS SPILLED.  TOM CALLED AND CONSULTED WITH NICK MCQUAY, CUMMING'S GENERAL MANAGER, AND THEN TOLD THE DRIVER TO TAKE THE TRUCK TO THE CUMMINGS LOST HILLS YARD ABOUT LOCATED 30 MILES NORTH OF TAFT. NICK THEN PLACED A CALL TO ME, TIM VAUGHN, SAFETY DIRECTOR, AND RELAYED THAT WE HAD A LEAKING TANK BUT HAD STOPPED THE LEAK AND THE TRUCK WAS HEADED TO OUR LOST HILLS YARD TO UNLOAD INTO A POLY TANK THAT WOULD BE DELIVERED THERE FOR THAT PURPOSE.  A SHORT TIME LATER I RECEIVED A SECOND CALL FROM NICK SAYING THAT TOM HAD BEEN CONTACTED BY THE TAFT POLICE DEPARTMENT RELATING THAT A TRUCK HAD SPILLED SOMETHING ON THE ROAD AND WANTED TO KNOW IF IT WAS ONE OF OURS.  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE POLICE AND ASKED THEM ABOUT THE SITUATION WHILE NICK CALLED THE DRIVER DIRECTLY FOR A FIRST-HAND REPORT. WHEN NICK VERIFIED TO THAT THE SPILL WAS OURS I AGAIN CALLED THE POLICE AND TOLD THEM THAT THE SPILL WAS FROM OUT TRUCK AND THAT IT WAS HYDROCHLORIC ACID SOLUTION.  I IN TURN CALLED ACTI (ADVANCED CLEANUP TECHNOLOGIES, INC.), REQUESTED A HAZMAT CREW AND HEADED TO TAFT TO INVESTIGATE THE SITUATION. AFTER SPEAKING WITH THE TAFT FIRE DEPARTMENT AND DAN STARKEY WITH KERN COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL HEALED SERVICES AT THE SCENE, I LEFT FOR OUR LOST HILLS YARD TO MEET WITH THE DRIVER WHERE I WAS INFORMED THAT THE REMAINDER OF THE LOAD, APPROXIMATELY 2,495 GALLONS, HAD SPILLED ONTO THE GROUND IN OUR YARD BEFORE IT COULD TRANSFERRED TO THE POLY TANK.  I THEN CALLED THE ACTI AND SPOKE WITH ROBERT, ONE OF THEIR EMPLOYEES WORKING AT THE SPILL SITE IN TAFT AND ASKED HIM TO RELAY TO DAN STARKEY OF THE ADDITIONAL SPILL..  I THEN IMMEDIATELY CALLED CALPI, INC., REQUESTING THAT THEY CLEAN UP THE SPILL AT OUR LOST HILLS YARD.
